<p><strong>Interpretation:</strong></p>
<p>Drama has consistently been the most dominant genre across all decades, representing roughly 20-25% of all films produced. Comedy also maintains a strong presence as the second most common genre for most of the timeline, though it experienced a decline from roughly 13% in the 1990s to roughly 10-11% in the 2010s and 2020s. This stability in the top two spots suggests a foundational audience interest in character-driven stories and light-hearted entertainment.</p>
<p>However, the other genres demonstrate more significant shifts. For example, Action films were a top-five genre in the 1990s but dropped out of the top five in the 2000s and did not return in subsequent decades. The 2000s saw the emergence of Documentary as a top genre (replacing Action), while the 2010s marked the peak of Documentary films, where they accounted for over 10% of the mix.</p>
<p>By the 2020s, the landscape shifted again: Horror emerged as a new top-five contender. Contrary to previous trends, Thriller has grown in prominence, approaching the popularity of Comedy, though Comedy retains the second position. Overall, the chart shows that while Drama remains the cultural constant, the secondary positions shift dynamically between Romance, Thriller, Documentary, and Horror in response to changing industry trends.</p>
