<p><strong>Interpretation:</strong></p>
<p><a href="#fig-budget-revenue-correlation" class="quarto-xref">Figure 10</a> reveals a <strong>strong positive correlation</strong> between a film’s inflation-adjusted budget and its worldwide gross revenue, with a Pearson correlation coefficient of approximately 0.70–0.75. This stands in stark contrast to the near-zero correlation observed between budget and IMDb rating in the previous section.</p>
<p>Several key observations emerge from this analysis:</p>
<ol type="1">
<li><p><strong>Strong Linear Relationship</strong>: The upward-sloping regression line (red) demonstrates that, on average, films with higher budgets tend to generate higher box office revenues. This relationship is visually apparent and statistically significant.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Break-Even Analysis</strong>: The black dashed line represents the break-even point where gross revenue equals the production budget. Most data points cluster above this line, indicating that the majority of films in our dataset recouped their production costs at the box office. However, it’s important to note that this does not account for marketing costs (often 50-100% of the production budget) or distribution fees, meaning true profitability is harder to determine.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Variance at Higher Budgets</strong>: While the correlation is strong, there is considerable variance, especially at higher budget levels. Some high-budget films ($100M+) achieve extraordinary returns (appearing well above the regression line), while others underperform relative to their investment. This variance reflects the inherent risk in blockbuster filmmaking—while big budgets can lead to big returns, they can also result in significant losses.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Low-Budget Outliers</strong>: Several low-budget films (below $10M) show remarkable returns, appearing far above the break-even line. These represent the “indie success stories”—films that achieved commercial success disproportionate to their modest investments, often through word-of-mouth, critical acclaim, or viral marketing.</p></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Key Takeaway</strong>: While money cannot buy audience appreciation (as shown in Q3), it does correlate strongly with commercial performance. This makes intuitive sense: larger budgets enable wider theatrical releases, more extensive marketing campaigns, bigger stars, and higher production values that attract audiences to theaters. However, the scatter around the trend line reminds us that financial success is never guaranteed—storytelling, timing, and market conditions all play crucial roles.</p>
</section>
<section id="q4-how-has-the-typical-duration-of-feature-films-evolved-over-the-last-three-decades" class="level2" data-number="3.5">
<h2 data-number="3.5"><span class="header-section-number">3.5</span> Q4: How has the typical duration of feature films evolved over the last three decades?</h2>
<p>Have you ever felt that movies are getting longer? This analysis investigates whether there is data to support this common perception. We plot the average movie duration per year to see if a trend emerges.</p>
<div id="cell-fig-duration-evolution" class="cell" data-execution_count="6">
<details class="code-fold">
<summary>Code</summary>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb5"><pre class="sourceCode python cell-code"><code class="sourceCode python"><span id="cb5-1"><a href="#cb5-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Calculate average duration per year</span></span>
<span id="cb5-2"><a href="#cb5-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>avg_duration_per_year <span class="op">=</span> data.groupby(data[<span class="st">&#39;release_date&#39;</span>].dt.year)[<span class="st">&#39;duration_minutes&#39;</span>].mean().reset_index()</span>
