<p><strong>Interpretation:</strong></p>
<p><a href="#fig-duration-evolution" class="quarto-xref">Figure 11</a> shows that the average duration of films has gradually increased over the last 3 decades. While films averaged around 102–104 minutes in the early 1990s, in recent years the average has more frequently reached 106–108 minutes, with some peaks even higher.</p>
<p>A notable exception emerges between approximately 2004 and 2012, during which time the average runtime decreases by several minutes compared to preceding and subsequent periods. This decline could be due to a number of factors, such as the increased popularity of mid-budget commercial comedies and action films, which tend to be shorter, as well as increased studio pressure to reduce runtimes in order to fit in more daily theatrical showings. There was also a shift towards faster-paced storytelling during the early 2000s. There were also fewer very long ‘epic-style’ releases during this period than in the later 2010s, which may have contributed to the lower averages.</p>
<p>Although there are yearly fluctuations, likely due to changes in sample size or variations in genre popularity, the overall regression trend line confirms a steady increase throughout the period.</p>
<p>This rise is modest rather than dramatic, but it is consistent, indicating that films today are generally a few minutes longer than those produced in the 1990s. This shift may reflect broader industry trends, such as the growth of franchise-based ‘event movies’, which often have longer narratives. The expansion of streaming platforms may also be a contributing factor: without the physical constraints imposed by VHS, DVDs or theatrical scheduling, filmmakers have greater freedom to determine runtime.</p>
<p>Overall, the data supports the idea that films have become slightly longer over time. While the increase is not extreme, it signals a shift in storytelling practices, with modern productions tending to embrace more complex or expansive narratives than in previous decades.</p>
</section>
<section id="q5-which-countries-have-dominated-global-film-production" class="level2" data-number="3.6">
<h2 data-number="3.6"><span class="header-section-number">3.6</span> Q5: Which countries have dominated global film production?</h2>
<p>To understand the geographical landscape of the film industry, we identify the top movie-producing countries for each decade (from the 1990s to the 2020s). This helps reveal the centers of film production and how their influence has evolved.</p>
<div id="cell-fig-country-production" class="cell" data-execution_count="7">
<details class="code-fold">
<summary>Code</summary>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb6"><pre class="sourceCode python cell-code"><code class="sourceCode python"><span id="cb6-1"><a href="#cb6-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># The &#39;countries_origin&#39; is a string representation of a list. We need to parse it.</span></span>
