<section id="methods" class="level1" data-number="4">
<h1 data-number="4"><span class="header-section-number">4</span> Methods</h1>
<p>For questions involving temporal trends (budget and duration evolution), we used line charts with trend lines. For categorical comparisons (genres and countries across decades), we utilized bar charts and proportional analysis. For the relationship between continuous variables (budget and rating), we applied statistical correlation measures as detailed below.</p>
<section id="pearson-correlation-coefficient" class="level2" data-number="4.1">
<h2 data-number="4.1"><span class="header-section-number">4.1</span> Pearson Correlation Coefficient</h2>
<p>To answer the question, “To what extent does financial investment (budget) influence audience reception (IMDb rating)?”, we used the <strong>Pearson correlation coefficient</strong>.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Why this method?</strong> The Pearson correlation coefficient (r) is a measure of linear association between two continuous variables. It is the most common method for measuring correlation and is ideal for understanding both the strength and direction of a relationship. Our goal was to see if a linear relationship exists where higher budgets correspond to higher ratings.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Assumptions</strong>: The key assumptions for Pearson correlation are that the variables are approximately normally distributed and that the relationship between them is linear. Our EDA scatter plot (<a href="#fig-budget-rating-correlation" class="quarto-xref">Figure 9</a> in the EDA section) showed that while the relationship is weak, it doesn’t appear to be strongly non-linear. We also used a log scale for the budget to handle the wide range of values, which helps in visualizing the linear trend.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>How it answers the question</strong>: The coefficient ranges from -1 (perfect negative linear correlation) to +1 (perfect positive linear correlation), with 0 indicating no linear correlation. By calculating this value, we can quantitatively assess the “money vs. quality” debate.</p></li>
</ul>
