<span id="cb10-284"><a href="#cb10-284" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>sns.lineplot(data<span class="op">=</span>budget_evolution_melted, x<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;year&#39;</span>, y<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;Amount&#39;</span>, hue<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;Budget Type&#39;</span>, ax<span class="op">=</span>ax, marker<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;o&#39;</span>, palette<span class="op">=</span>[<span class="st">&#39;purple&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;orange&#39;</span>])</span>
<span id="cb10-285"><a href="#cb10-285" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-286"><a href="#cb10-286" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Add a trend line for the Real Budget</span></span>
<span id="cb10-287"><a href="#cb10-287" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>sns.regplot(data<span class="op">=</span>budget_evolution, x<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;year&#39;</span>, y<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;Real Budget (2025 USD)&#39;</span>, ax<span class="op">=</span>ax, scatter<span class="op">=</span><span class="va">False</span>, color<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;red&#39;</span>, line_kws<span class="op">=</span>{<span class="st">&#39;linestyle&#39;</span>:<span class="st">&#39;--&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;linewidth&#39;</span>: <span class="fl">1.5</span>, <span class="st">&#39;label&#39;</span>: <span class="st">&#39;Trend (Real)&#39;</span>})</span>
<span id="cb10-288"><a href="#cb10-288" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-289"><a href="#cb10-289" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Customize plot</span></span>
<span id="cb10-290"><a href="#cb10-290" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_title(<span class="st">&quot;Median Movie Budget Evolution (1990-2025)&quot;</span>, </span>
<span id="cb10-291"><a href="#cb10-291" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>             fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">16</span>, fontweight<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;bold&#39;</span>, pad<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">15</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-292"><a href="#cb10-292" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_xlabel(<span class="st">&quot;Year&quot;</span>, fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">12</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-293"><a href="#cb10-293" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_ylabel(<span class="st">&quot;Median Budget (in USD)&quot;</span>, fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">12</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-294"><a href="#cb10-294" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.grid(<span class="va">True</span>, alpha<span class="op">=</span><span class="fl">0.5</span>, linestyle<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;--&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-295"><a href="#cb10-295" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.get_yaxis().set_major_formatter(plt.FuncFormatter(<span class="kw">lambda</span> x, p: <span class="ss">f&#39;$</span><span class="sc">{</span>x<span class="op">/</span><span class="dv">1_000_000</span><span class="sc">:.0f}</span><span class="ss">M&#39;</span>))</span>
<span id="cb10-296"><a href="#cb10-296" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.legend()</span>
<span id="cb10-297"><a href="#cb10-297" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-298"><a href="#cb10-298" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>plt.tight_layout()</span>
<span id="cb10-299"><a href="#cb10-299" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>plt.show()</span>
<span id="cb10-300"><a href="#cb10-300" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="in">```</span></span>
<span id="cb10-301"><a href="#cb10-301" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-302"><a href="#cb10-302" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>**Interpretation:**</span>
<span id="cb10-303"><a href="#cb10-303" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-304"><a href="#cb10-304" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>@fig-budget-evolution reveals a surprising divergence between nominal spending and real purchasing power. While the nominal budget (purple line) suggests a gradual increase from roughly $11 million in 1990 to peaks of $30 million in recent years, the inflation-adjusted &quot;Real Budget&quot; (gold line, Base 2025) tells a starkly different story. Contrary to the expectation that costs have skyrocketed, the regression line indicates a clear downward trend in real median budgets over the 35-year period.</span>
<span id="cb10-305"><a href="#cb10-305" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-306"><a href="#cb10-306" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>In real terms (2025 dollars), median budgets actually peaked in the late 1990s, reaching highs of over $35 million. Since then, despite significant volatility, the purchasing power allocated to the median film has steadily eroded, dropping to approximately $19 million by 2025.</span>
<span id="cb10-307"><a href="#cb10-307" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-308"><a href="#cb10-308" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>Several factors may explain this real-term decline. First, the democratization of digital filmmaking tools may have lowered the barrier to entry, allowing more low-to-mid-budget films to be produced more cheaply. Second, the industry may be experiencing a &quot;hollowing out&quot; effect: while massive blockbusters (not captured by the median) have ballooned in cost, the &quot;middle-class&quot; movie has faced tightening budget constraints.</span>
<span id="cb10-309"><a href="#cb10-309" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-310"><a href="#cb10-310" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>The graph also highlights distinct periods of volatility. A sharp dip is visible around the 2008 financial crisis and again in the mid-2010s. Interestingly, while there was a significant spike in real spending around 2022–2023 (likely a post-pandemic production surge) values have since corrected downward. Overall, the analysis overturns the assumption that filmmaking is becoming universally more expensive; instead, it suggests that outside of mega-blockbusters, the typical film is being made with a leaner real-world budget than it was three decades ago.</span>
<span id="cb10-311"><a href="#cb10-311" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-312"><a href="#cb10-312" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">## Q3: To what extent does financial investment (budget) influence audience reception (IMDb rating)?</span></span>
<span id="cb10-313"><a href="#cb10-313" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-314"><a href="#cb10-314" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>A central question for any film producer is whether more money leads to a better movie. We investigate this by plotting **inflation-adjusted budgets** against their IMDb ratings. Given that budgets span several orders of magnitude, we use a logarithmic scale for the budget axis to better visualize the relationship.</span>
<span id="cb10-315"><a href="#cb10-315" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-316"><a href="#cb10-316" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>quarto-executable-code-5450563D</span>
<span id="cb10-317"><a href="#cb10-317" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-318"><a href="#cb10-318" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="in">```python</span></span>
<span id="cb10-319"><a href="#cb10-319" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#| label: fig-budget-rating-correlation</span></span>
<span id="cb10-320"><a href="#cb10-320" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#| fig-cap: &quot;Scatter plot of inflation-adjusted movie budget vs. IMDb rating&quot;</span></span>
<span id="cb10-321"><a href="#cb10-321" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-322"><a href="#cb10-322" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Filter out rows with missing budget or rating for this analysis</span></span>
<span id="cb10-323"><a href="#cb10-323" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>budget_rating_data <span class="op">=</span> data.dropna(subset<span class="op">=</span>[<span class="st">&#39;budget_adjusted&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;rating&#39;</span>])</span>
<span id="cb10-324"><a href="#cb10-324" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-325"><a href="#cb10-325" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Create the plot</span></span>
<span id="cb10-326"><a href="#cb10-326" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>fig, ax <span class="op">=</span> plt.subplots(figsize<span class="op">=</span>(<span class="fl">8.25</span>, <span class="fl">5.25</span>))</span>
<span id="cb10-327"><a href="#cb10-327" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-328"><a href="#cb10-328" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>sns.regplot(data<span class="op">=</span>budget_rating_data, x<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;budget_adjusted&#39;</span>, y<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;rating&#39;</span>,</span>
<span id="cb10-329"><a href="#cb10-329" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>            ax<span class="op">=</span>ax, scatter_kws<span class="op">=</span>{<span class="st">&#39;alpha&#39;</span>: <span class="fl">0.2</span>, <span class="st">&#39;s&#39;</span>: <span class="dv">20</span>},</span>
<span id="cb10-330"><a href="#cb10-330" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>            line_kws<span class="op">=</span>{<span class="st">&#39;color&#39;</span>: <span class="st">&#39;red&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;linewidth&#39;</span>: <span class="dv">2</span>})</span>
<span id="cb10-331"><a href="#cb10-331" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-332"><a href="#cb10-332" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Customize plot</span></span>
<span id="cb10-333"><a href="#cb10-333" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_xscale(<span class="st">&#39;log&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-334"><a href="#cb10-334" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_title(<span class="st">&quot;Correlation Between Real Budget and IMDb Rating&quot;</span>, </span>
<span id="cb10-335"><a href="#cb10-335" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>             fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">16</span>, fontweight<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;bold&#39;</span>, pad<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">15</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-336"><a href="#cb10-336" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_xlabel(<span class="st">&quot;Budget (Inflation Adjusted to 2025 USD, log scale)&quot;</span>, fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">12</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-337"><a href="#cb10-337" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_ylabel(<span class="st">&quot;IMDb Rating&quot;</span>, fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">12</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-338"><a href="#cb10-338" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.grid(<span class="va">True</span>, alpha<span class="op">=</span><span class="fl">0.3</span>, linestyle<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;--&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-339"><a href="#cb10-339" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-340"><a href="#cb10-340" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Add correlation coefficient</span></span>
<span id="cb10-341"><a href="#cb10-341" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>correlation <span class="op">=</span> budget_rating_data[<span class="st">&#39;budget_adjusted&#39;</span>].corr(budget_rating_data[<span class="st">&#39;rating&#39;</span>])</span>
<span id="cb10-342"><a href="#cb10-342" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.text(<span class="fl">0.05</span>, <span class="fl">0.95</span>, <span class="ss">f&#39;Pearson Correlation: </span><span class="sc">{</span>correlation<span class="sc">:.3f}</span><span class="ss">&#39;</span>, </span>
<span id="cb10-343"><a href="#cb10-343" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>        transform<span class="op">=</span>ax.transAxes, fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">11</span>,</span>
<span id="cb10-344"><a href="#cb10-344" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>        verticalalignment<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;top&#39;</span>,</span>
<span id="cb10-345"><a href="#cb10-345" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>        bbox<span class="op">=</span><span class="bu">dict</span>(boxstyle<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;round&#39;</span>, facecolor<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;wheat&#39;</span>, alpha<span class="op">=</span><span class="fl">0.5</span>))</span>
<span id="cb10-346"><a href="#cb10-346" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-347"><a href="#cb10-347" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>plt.tight_layout()</span>
<span id="cb10-348"><a href="#cb10-348" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>plt.show()</span>
<span id="cb10-349"><a href="#cb10-349" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="in">```</span></span>
<span id="cb10-350"><a href="#cb10-350" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-351"><a href="#cb10-351" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>**Interpretation:**</span>
<span id="cb10-352"><a href="#cb10-352" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-353"><a href="#cb10-353" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>@fig-budget-rating-correlation demonstrates that there is an extremely weak relationship between a film&#39;s inflation-adjusted budget and its IMDb rating. While the regression curve (red line) shows a slight upward inflection at the highest budget levels, the overall pattern is largely flat. This visual observation is confirmed by the low Pearson correlation coefficient of 0.140, indicating only a minimal linear association between financial investment and audience reception.</span>
<span id="cb10-354"><a href="#cb10-354" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-355"><a href="#cb10-355" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>The dispersion of points across the logarithmic budget scale further supports this conclusion. Highly rated films (with scores above 7 or 8) appear across the entire financial spectrum, ranging from micro-budget productions costing less than $10,000 (roughly $10^4$) to massive blockbusters exceeding $200–300 million. Likewise, low-rated films are distributed widely. This significant vertical spread suggests that audience appreciation depends far more on qualitative factors (such as storytelling, acting, and originality) than on the magnitude of resources spent.</span>
<span id="cb10-356"><a href="#cb10-356" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-357"><a href="#cb10-357" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>However, a subtle pattern emerges at the extreme right of the plot: films with the highest inflation-adjusted budgets (approaching $10^8$ and above) tend to avoid the lowest rating range (scores below 4). In other words, while spending massive amounts does not guarantee a masterpiece, it appears to reduce the likelihood of a film being critically panned. This &quot;floor effect&quot; likely results from the extensive professional oversight, technical standards, and production value inherent in large-scale studio projects.</span>
<span id="cb10-358"><a href="#cb10-358" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-359"><a href="#cb10-359" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>Overall, this analysis confirms that larger budgets do not strictly correlate with higher ratings. The data highlights the critical success of numerous low-to-mid-budget films, proving that creativity can rival visual spectacle. For producers, this emphasizes that while money can ensure technical competence, it cannot buy audience satisfaction.</span>
<span id="cb10-360"><a href="#cb10-360" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-361"><a href="#cb10-361" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">## Q3a: Is there a correlation between a film&#39;s budget and its box office revenue?</span></span>
<span id="cb10-362"><a href="#cb10-362" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-363"><a href="#cb10-363" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>While budget may not predict audience ratings, it might be a better predictor of commercial success. We now examine the relationship between a film&#39;s **inflation-adjusted budget** and its **inflation-adjusted worldwide gross revenue**. This analysis helps determine whether higher investments typically yield higher financial returns.</span>
<span id="cb10-364"><a href="#cb10-364" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-365"><a href="#cb10-365" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>quarto-executable-code-5450563D</span>
<span id="cb10-366"><a href="#cb10-366" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-367"><a href="#cb10-367" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="in">```python</span></span>
<span id="cb10-368"><a href="#cb10-368" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#| label: fig-budget-revenue-correlation</span></span>
<span id="cb10-369"><a href="#cb10-369" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#| fig-cap: &quot;Scatter plot of inflation-adjusted movie budget vs. worldwide gross revenue&quot;</span></span>
<span id="cb10-370"><a href="#cb10-370" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-371"><a href="#cb10-371" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Apply inflation adjustment to gross_worldwide</span></span>
<span id="cb10-372"><a href="#cb10-372" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="kw">def</span> adjust_gross_for_inflation(row):</span>
<span id="cb10-373"><a href="#cb10-373" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    year <span class="op">=</span> row[<span class="st">&#39;release_date&#39;</span>].year</span>
<span id="cb10-374"><a href="#cb10-374" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="cf">if</span> year <span class="kw">in</span> cpi_data <span class="kw">and</span> pd.notna(row[<span class="st">&#39;gross_worldwide&#39;</span>]):</span>
<span id="cb10-375"><a href="#cb10-375" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>        <span class="cf">return</span> row[<span class="st">&#39;gross_worldwide&#39;</span>] <span class="op">*</span> (cpi_data[<span class="dv">2025</span>] <span class="op">/</span> cpi_data[year])</span>
<span id="cb10-376"><a href="#cb10-376" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="cf">return</span> row[<span class="st">&#39;gross_worldwide&#39;</span>]</span>
<span id="cb10-377"><a href="#cb10-377" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-378"><a href="#cb10-378" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data[<span class="st">&#39;gross_adjusted&#39;</span>] <span class="op">=</span> data.<span class="bu">apply</span>(adjust_gross_for_inflation, axis<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">1</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-379"><a href="#cb10-379" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-380"><a href="#cb10-380" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Filter out rows with missing budget or gross for this analysis</span></span>
<span id="cb10-381"><a href="#cb10-381" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>budget_revenue_data <span class="op">=</span> data.dropna(subset<span class="op">=</span>[<span class="st">&#39;budget_adjusted&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;gross_adjusted&#39;</span>])</span>
<span id="cb10-382"><a href="#cb10-382" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-383"><a href="#cb10-383" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Create the plot</span></span>
<span id="cb10-384"><a href="#cb10-384" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>fig, ax <span class="op">=</span> plt.subplots(figsize<span class="op">=</span>(<span class="fl">8.25</span>, <span class="fl">5.25</span>))</span>
<span id="cb10-385"><a href="#cb10-385" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-386"><a href="#cb10-386" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>sns.regplot(data<span class="op">=</span>budget_revenue_data, x<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;budget_adjusted&#39;</span>, y<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;gross_adjusted&#39;</span>,</span>
<span id="cb10-387"><a href="#cb10-387" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>            ax<span class="op">=</span>ax, scatter_kws<span class="op">=</span>{<span class="st">&#39;alpha&#39;</span>: <span class="fl">0.3</span>, <span class="st">&#39;s&#39;</span>: <span class="dv">20</span>},</span>
<span id="cb10-388"><a href="#cb10-388" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>            line_kws<span class="op">=</span>{<span class="st">&#39;color&#39;</span>: <span class="st">&#39;red&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;linewidth&#39;</span>: <span class="dv">2</span>})</span>
<span id="cb10-389"><a href="#cb10-389" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-390"><a href="#cb10-390" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Add a diagonal reference line (break-even line where gross = budget)</span></span>
<span id="cb10-391"><a href="#cb10-391" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>max_val <span class="op">=</span> <span class="bu">max</span>(budget_revenue_data[<span class="st">&#39;budget_adjusted&#39;</span>].<span class="bu">max</span>(), budget_revenue_data[<span class="st">&#39;gross_adjusted&#39;</span>].<span class="bu">max</span>())</span>
<span id="cb10-392"><a href="#cb10-392" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.plot([<span class="fl">1e4</span>, max_val], [<span class="fl">1e4</span>, max_val], <span class="st">&#39;k--&#39;</span>, linewidth<span class="op">=</span><span class="fl">1.5</span>, alpha<span class="op">=</span><span class="fl">0.8</span>, label<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;Break-even (Gross = Budget)&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-393"><a href="#cb10-393" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-394"><a href="#cb10-394" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Customize plot</span></span>
<span id="cb10-395"><a href="#cb10-395" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_xscale(<span class="st">&#39;log&#39;</span>)</span>
