<span id="cb10-574"><a href="#cb10-574" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>**Interpretation:**</span>
<span id="cb10-575"><a href="#cb10-575" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-576"><a href="#cb10-576" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>The bar chart in @fig-top-rated-countries is revealing a clear hierarchy. Once again, it shows that the United States is the most dominant producer of top-rated films, contributing far more highly-rated movies than any other country in our analysis. However, other elements should be taken as a source of quality. A second tier of countries, which includes the United Kingdom, Japan and India as well, consistently contributes a significant number of critically acclaimed films. The list also includes other nations such as France, South Korea, and Germany, proving that high-rated films originate from diverse cultural and geographical centers.</span>
<span id="cb10-577"><a href="#cb10-577" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-578"><a href="#cb10-578" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>This finding provides a nuanced answer to our question. While the highest-rated films do consistently come from the United States in terms of volume, critical acclaim is by no means exclusive to it. The strong showing from the UK aligns with its established industry and close ties to Hollywood. More importantly, the significant contributions from Japan (renowned for its auteurs and animation), India (with its massive Bollywood output), and South Korea (a recent powerhouse in global cinema) indicate that cinematic excellence can be considered as a global achievement. This suggests that while the Hollywood system is effective at producing a pretty high volume of popular and successful films, distinct cultural voices from around the world are equally capable of creating works that resonate deeply with global audiences.</span>
<span id="cb10-579"><a href="#cb10-579" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-580"><a href="#cb10-580" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu"># Methods</span></span>
<span id="cb10-581"><a href="#cb10-581" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-582"><a href="#cb10-582" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>For questions involving temporal trends (budget and duration evolution), we used line charts with trend lines. For categorical comparisons (genres and countries across decades), we utilized bar charts and proportional analysis. For the relationship between continuous variables (budget and rating), we applied statistical correlation measures as detailed below.</span>
<span id="cb10-583"><a href="#cb10-583" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-584"><a href="#cb10-584" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">## Pearson Correlation Coefficient</span></span>
<span id="cb10-585"><a href="#cb10-585" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-586"><a href="#cb10-586" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>To answer the question, &quot;To what extent does financial investment (budget) influence audience reception (IMDb rating)?&quot;, we used the **Pearson correlation coefficient**.</span>
<span id="cb10-587"><a href="#cb10-587" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-588"><a href="#cb10-588" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Why this method?** The Pearson correlation coefficient (r) is a measure of linear association between two continuous variables. It is the most common method for measuring correlation and is ideal for understanding both the strength and direction of a relationship. Our goal was to see if a linear relationship exists where higher budgets correspond to higher ratings.</span>
<span id="cb10-589"><a href="#cb10-589" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-590"><a href="#cb10-590" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Assumptions**: The key assumptions for Pearson correlation are that the variables are approximately normally distributed and that the relationship between them is linear. Our EDA scatter plot (@fig-budget-rating-correlation in the EDA section) showed that while the relationship is weak, it doesn&#39;t appear to be strongly non-linear. We also used a log scale for the budget to handle the wide range of values, which helps in visualizing the linear trend.</span>
<span id="cb10-591"><a href="#cb10-591" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-592"><a href="#cb10-592" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**How it answers the question**: The coefficient ranges from -1 (perfect negative linear correlation) to +1 (perfect positive linear correlation), with 0 indicating no linear correlation. By calculating this value, we can quantitatively assess the &quot;money vs. quality&quot; debate.</span>
<span id="cb10-593"><a href="#cb10-593" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-594"><a href="#cb10-594" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>quarto-executable-code-5450563D</span>
<span id="cb10-595"><a href="#cb10-595" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-596"><a href="#cb10-596" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="in">```python</span></span>
<span id="cb10-597"><a href="#cb10-597" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#| label: tbl-correlation-calculation</span></span>
<span id="cb10-598"><a href="#cb10-598" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#| tbl-cap: &quot;Pearson correlation between movie budget and IMDb rating&quot;</span></span>
<span id="cb10-599"><a href="#cb10-599" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-600"><a href="#cb10-600" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Filter out rows with missing budget or rating for this analysis</span></span>
<span id="cb10-601"><a href="#cb10-601" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>budget_rating_data <span class="op">=</span> data.dropna(subset<span class="op">=</span>[<span class="st">&#39;budget&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;rating&#39;</span>])</span>
<span id="cb10-602"><a href="#cb10-602" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-603"><a href="#cb10-603" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Calculate the Pearson correlation</span></span>
<span id="cb10-604"><a href="#cb10-604" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>correlation <span class="op">=</span> budget_rating_data[<span class="st">&#39;budget&#39;</span>].corr(budget_rating_data[<span class="st">&#39;rating&#39;</span>])</span>
<span id="cb10-605"><a href="#cb10-605" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-606"><a href="#cb10-606" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Create a DataFrame for display</span></span>
<span id="cb10-607"><a href="#cb10-607" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>correlation_df <span class="op">=</span> pd.DataFrame({</span>
<span id="cb10-608"><a href="#cb10-608" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="st">&quot;Metric&quot;</span>: [<span class="st">&quot;Pearson Correlation (r)&quot;</span>],</span>
<span id="cb10-609"><a href="#cb10-609" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="st">&quot;Value&quot;</span>: [<span class="ss">f&quot;</span><span class="sc">{</span>correlation<span class="sc">:.4f}</span><span class="ss">&quot;</span>]</span>
<span id="cb10-610"><a href="#cb10-610" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>})</span>
<span id="cb10-611"><a href="#cb10-611" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-612"><a href="#cb10-612" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="bu">print</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Pearson Correlation Between Movie Budget and IMDb Rating&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-613"><a href="#cb10-613" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="bu">print</span>(correlation_df.to_string(index<span class="op">=</span><span class="va">False</span>))</span>
<span id="cb10-614"><a href="#cb10-614" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="in">```</span></span>
<span id="cb10-615"><a href="#cb10-615" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-616"><a href="#cb10-616" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">## Linear Regression Line</span></span>
<span id="cb10-617"><a href="#cb10-617" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-618"><a href="#cb10-618" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>In addition to the Pearson correlation, we visualized the relationship between budget and rating using a **linear regression line** on our scatter plot (@fig-budget-rating-correlation).</span>
<span id="cb10-619"><a href="#cb10-619" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-620"><a href="#cb10-620" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Why this method?** A regression line provides a visual representation of the trend in the data. It is the line that best fits the data points, minimizing the overall distance from the points to the line. This makes it an excellent tool for visually assessing the direction and strength of a linear relationship.</span>
<span id="cb10-621"><a href="#cb10-621" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-622"><a href="#cb10-622" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**How it complements the analysis**: While the Pearson coefficient gives a single number, the regression line on the scatter plot shows how the trend plays out across the entire range of data. The flatness of the line in our plot visually confirms the very weak correlation indicated by the coefficient, making the finding more intuitive and impactful.</span>
<span id="cb10-623"><a href="#cb10-623" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-624"><a href="#cb10-624" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu"># Findings and Discussion</span></span>
<span id="cb10-625"><a href="#cb10-625" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-626"><a href="#cb10-626" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>Our exploratory data analysis (EDA) revealed several key trends in the global film industry from 1990 to 2025, providing insights into economic and cultural evolution.</span>
<span id="cb10-627"><a href="#cb10-627" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-628"><a href="#cb10-628" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Finding**: The Pearson correlation coefficient between a movie’s inflation-adjusted budget and its IMDb rating is 0.140, as calculated in Table 1.</span>
<span id="cb10-629"><a href="#cb10-629" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Interpretation**: A correlation coefficient of 0.140 indicates an extremely weak positive linear relationship. While this suggests no meaningful linear association between financial investment and audience satisfaction, the scatter plot reveals a subtle nuance: while high budgets do not guarantee high ratings, they appear to prevent extremely low ones. There is a visible “floor effect” where high-budget films (approaching 108) rarely fall into the lowest rating categories.</span>
<span id="cb10-630"><a href="#cb10-630" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Connection to Research Question**: This directly answers our third sub-question. While there might be a perception that big-budget films are “better,” our data does not support this. The lack of a strong correlation implies that financial investment cannot be considered a reliable predictor of audience appreciation, though it may act as a safeguard against technical failure.</span>
<span id="cb10-631"><a href="#cb10-631" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Domain Context**: This finding is significant for the film industry. It challenges the “blockbuster formula” that relies on massive budgets to generate hits. It suggests that qualitative factors, such as script quality and acting, are the critical drivers of reception. It also validates the success of low-budget independent films that achieve high ratings, proving that creativity can triumph over capital.</span>
<span id="cb10-632"><a href="#cb10-632" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-633"><a href="#cb10-633" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>Beyond the budget-rating relationship, our EDA uncovered other important industry patterns:</span>
<span id="cb10-634"><a href="#cb10-634" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-635"><a href="#cb10-635" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Genre Evolution**: Drama has remained the undisputed dominant genre (~25%) across all decades. Comedy has seen a slight decline, dropping from ~13% in the 90s to ~10-11% in the 2010s and 2020s. We observed dynamic shifts elsewhere: Documentaries surged specifically in the 2010s, accounting for over 10% of the mix, while the 2020s have been defined by the emergence of Horror as a top-five genre.</span>
<span id="cb10-636"><a href="#cb10-636" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Economic Trends**: Contrary to the assumption that filmmaking is becoming universally more expensive, our inflation-adjusted analysis reveals a downward trend in real median budgets since the late 1990s. While nominal costs have risen to approximately $30 million, the real purchasing power (2025 USD) allocated to the median film has eroded, dropping to approximately $19 million by 2025.</span>
<span id="cb10-637"><a href="#cb10-637" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Quality vs. Cost**: We calculated a negligible correlation (0.140) between inflation-adjusted budgets and IMDb ratings. This confirms that financial investment does not guarantee audience appreciation, though the data suggests a “floor effect” where high budgets help prevent extremely low ratings by ensuring technical competence.</span>
<span id="cb10-638"><a href="#cb10-638" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Film Duration**: We found a slight but consistent upward trend in average movie duration, moving from 102–104 minutes in the 1990s to 106–108 minutes currently, supporting the perception that storytelling formats are lengthening.</span>
<span id="cb10-639"><a href="#cb10-639" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Global Production Landscape**: The United States maintained dominant production volume, but the landscape is globalizing. The consistent presence of the UK, along with the emergence of China and strong showings from India and Japan, highlights a diversifying market where critical acclaim is increasingly distributed worldwide.</span>
<span id="cb10-640"><a href="#cb10-640" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-641"><a href="#cb10-641" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>**Limitations**: It is important to note that correlation does not imply causation. Furthermore, the budget-rating analysis only measures a linear relationship; the slight “floor effect” observed suggests non-linear dynamics at the highest budget levels. Additionally, our findings regarding the “real” budget decline rely heavily on the accuracy of CPI adjustments and may not fully capture sector-specific inflation (e.g., the specific rising costs of CGI talent vs. general consumer goods).</span>
<span id="cb10-642"><a href="#cb10-642" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-643"><a href="#cb10-643" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu"># Conclusion</span></span>
<span id="cb10-644"><a href="#cb10-644" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-645"><a href="#cb10-645" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">## Summary</span></span>
<span id="cb10-646"><a href="#cb10-646" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-647"><a href="#cb10-647" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>This project set out to analyze the evolution of the global film industry from 1990 to 2025 by exploring trends in movie characteristics and audience preferences. Using a comprehensive IMDb dataset from Kaggle, we performed a thorough data cleaning process and conducted an exploratory data analysis to answer our key research questions.</span>
<span id="cb10-648"><a href="#cb10-648" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-649"><a href="#cb10-649" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>Our main findings reveal a dynamic and evolving industry:</span>
<span id="cb10-650"><a href="#cb10-650" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-651"><a href="#cb10-651" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Genre Trends**: While Drama remains the undisputed leader (~25% of production), Comedy has seen a steady decline in dominance. Documentaries experienced a surge in the 2000s and 2010s, while the 2020s have been defined by the consistent presence of Thriller and the emergence of Horror.</span>
<span id="cb10-652"><a href="#cb10-652" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Economic Shifts**: Contrasting with the assumption of rising costs, our inflation-adjusted analysis reveals a downward trend in real median budgets since the late 1990s. While nominal spending has risen, the purchasing power allocated to the typical film has eroded, suggesting a “hollowing out” of mid-budget productions in favor of low-cost entries and massive tentpoles.</span>
<span id="cb10-653"><a href="#cb10-653" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Quality vs. Cost**: We calculated a negligible correlation (0.140) between inflation-adjusted budgets and IMDb ratings. This confirms that financial investment does not guarantee audience appreciation, though the data suggests a “floor effect” where high budgets help prevent extremely low ratings by ensuring technical competence.</span>
<span id="cb10-654"><a href="#cb10-654" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Film Duration**: We found a slight but consistent upward trend in average movie duration, moving from 102–104 minutes in the 1990s to 106–108 minutes currently, supporting the perception that storytelling formats are lengthening.</span>
<span id="cb10-655"><a href="#cb10-655" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Global Production**: The United States continues to dominate volume, but the landscape is globalizing. The consistent output of the United Kingdom, combined with the emergence of China and strong showings from India and Japan, highlights a diversifying market where critical acclaim is increasingly distributed worldwide.</span>
<span id="cb10-656"><a href="#cb10-656" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-657"><a href="#cb10-657" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">## Limitations</span></span>
<span id="cb10-658"><a href="#cb10-658" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-659"><a href="#cb10-659" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>It is important to acknowledge the constraints of our analysis to contextualize our findings properly:</span>
<span id="cb10-660"><a href="#cb10-660" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-661"><a href="#cb10-661" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Data Bias**: The dataset is heavily skewed towards Hollywood and Western cinema. Consequently, our findings on “global” trends may not fully capture the nuances of film industries in other parts of the world, such as Asia, Africa, or South America, despite the presence of data from major hubs like India and China.</span>
<span id="cb10-662"><a href="#cb10-662" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Missing Data**: A significant number of films, particularly older or independent ones, were missing financial data (e.g., <span class="in">`budget`</span>, <span class="in">`gross_worldwide`</span>). While we handled this by excluding them from specific financial analyses, their absence could slightly skew the results toward better-documented, higher-profile releases.</span>
<span id="cb10-663"><a href="#cb10-663" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Inflation Adjustment Method**: Unlike previous analyses, this report did adjust financial data for inflation using the general Consumer Price Index (CPI-U). However, this index tracks the price of general consumer goods (like food and housing), not specific film production inputs. It does not account for the rapid, sector-specific inflation of costs related to CGI, specialized union labor, and star salaries. Therefore, our &quot;Real Budget&quot; calculations may still not fully reflect the true erosion of purchasing power within the industry.</span>
<span id="cb10-664"><a href="#cb10-664" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Subjective Ratings**: IMDb ratings are user-generated and can be influenced by cultural biases, targeted campaigns (e.g., “review bombing”), or the specific demographics of the platform’s user base.</span>
<span id="cb10-665"><a href="#cb10-665" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Methodological Scope**: Our analysis is exploratory in nature. While we have identified interesting correlations (or the lack thereof), we cannot establish causal relationships between variables.</span>
<span id="cb10-666"><a href="#cb10-666" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-667"><a href="#cb10-667" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu"># References</span></span>
