<section id="introduction" class="level1" data-number="1">
<h1 data-number="1">
<span class="header-section-number">1</span> Introduction
</h1>
<section id="overview-motivation" class="level2" data-number="1.1">
<h2 data-number="1.1" class="anchored" data-anchor-id="overview-motivation">
<span class="header-section-number">1.1</span> Overview &amp; Motivation
</h2>
<p>
Over the last few decades, the film industry has undergone major transformations, shaped by globalization, technological innovation and changing audience preferences. As students who grew up watching movies and series from many genres and countries, we have personally experienced these changes. This makes the topic not only interesting but also culturally relevant and close to us. Studying the evolution of cinema through data allows us to understand how entertainment reflects societal changes, technological progress, and shifting audience tastes. It is a topic that meaningfully connects culture, society, and data science.
</p>
</section>
<section id="project-goals" class="level2" data-number="1.2">
<h2 data-number="1.2" class="anchored" data-anchor-id="project-goals">
<span class="header-section-number">1.2</span> Project Goals
</h2>
<p>
The goal of this project is to analyze the evolution of the global film industry from 1990 to 2025. We focused on this specific timeframe to ensure data consistency and completeness, as financial records prior to 1990 are often fragmented, and to specifically capture the modern era defined by the digital revolution and the globalization of film markets. We aim to understand how public tastes and film characteristics such as, genre, budget, duration, and country of origin, have changed over time. This topic is relevant as it connects art, culture, and data science, allowing us to use data to explore historical and cultural trends in entertainment. By transforming creative aspects of cinema into measurable patterns, we can gain insights into how technology, audience preferences, and globalization have shaped the movies we watch today. The analysis will focus on exploratory data analysis (EDA) to identify major trends and correlations.
</p>
</section>
<section id="related-work" class="level2" data-number="1.3">
<h2 data-number="1.3" class="anchored" data-anchor-id="related-work">
<span class="header-section-number">1.3</span> Related Work
</h2>
<p>
Our project was inspired by several online analyses and discussions. For example, IMDb and Kaggle host many studies that explore genre evolution, variations in movie ratings over time, and Hollywood budget inflation. Academic discussions about the globalisation of cinema also highlight the growing impact of film industries such as Bollywood, Nollywood and East Asian cinema. Drawing on these references, we were able to structure our questions and identify the most relevant variables for understanding how the industry has progressed, such as genre, ratings, budgets and countries.
</p>
</section>
<section id="research-questions" class="level2" data-number="1.4">
<h2 data-number="1.4" class="anchored" data-anchor-id="research-questions">
<span class="header-section-number">1.4</span> Research Questions
</h2>
<p>
Our primary research question is: - How do public tastes and movie characteristics (such as genres, budgets, durations, and origins) vary across time in the global film industry between 1990 and 2025?
</p>
<p>
To address this, we will investigate the following sub-questions, each providing a different lens through which to view the industry’s evolution:
</p>
<ul>
<li>
<strong>Which film genres dominated each decade?</strong> This question helps us understand changing cultural tastes and identify which storytelling formats were most popular in different eras.
</li>
<li>
<strong>How have movie budgets evolved over time?</strong> Analyzing budget trends reveals the economic shifts in the film industry, from the rise of blockbusters to the impact of new technologies.
</li>
<li>
<strong>To what extent does financial investment (budget) influence audience reception (IMDb rating)?</strong> This explores whether higher financial investment typically translates into better audience reception, a key consideration for producers.
</li>
<li>
<strong>Is there a correlation between a film’s budget and its box office revenue?</strong> This explores whether higher financial investment typically translates into better revenue, another key consideration for producers.
</li>
<li>
<strong>How has the typical duration of feature films evolved over the last three decades?</strong> The answer to this question can reflect changes in storytelling norms and audience viewing habits.
</li>
<li>
<strong>Which countries have dominated global film production over different periods?</strong> This highlights the geographical shifts in filmmaking, showing the influence of globalization and the rise of new markets.
</li>
<li>
<strong>Do the highest-rated films consistently come from the same regions?</strong> This question examines whether critical acclaim is concentrated in specific cultural or geographical areas.
</li>
</ul>
</section>
</section>
<section id="data" class="level1" data-number="2">
<h1 data-number="2">
<span class="header-section-number">2</span> Data
</h1>
<section id="sources" class="level2" data-number="2.1">
<h2 data-number="2.1" class="anchored" data-anchor-id="sources">
<span class="header-section-number">2.1</span> Sources
</h2>
<p>
Our primary dataset was sourced from Kaggle: <strong>IMDb Movies from 1920 to 2025</strong>, published by Raed Addala. The data was accessed in November 2025. The dataset in CSV format is available at the following URL: <a href="https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/raedaddala/imdb-movies-from-1960-to-2023/data">https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/raedaddala/imdb-movies-from-1960-to-2023/data</a>.
</p>
</section>
<section id="description" class="level2" data-number="2.2">
<h2 data-number="2.2" class="anchored" data-anchor-id="description">
<span class="header-section-number">2.2</span> Description
</h2>
<section id="raw-data" class="level3" data-number="2.2.1">
<h3 data-number="2.2.1" class="anchored" data-anchor-id="raw-data">
<span class="header-section-number">2.2.1</span> Raw Data
</h3>
<p>
The original dataset obtained from Kaggle contains:
</p>
<ul>
<li>
<strong>Number of observations</strong>: ~60,000 movies
</li>
<li>
<strong>Number of variables</strong>: 23 columns
</li>
<li>
<strong>Time period</strong>: 1920 to 2025
</li>
<li>
<strong>Format</strong>: CSV file
</li>
<li>
<strong>Raw variables include</strong>:
<ul>
<li>
<code>title</code>: Movie title as a string
</li>
<li>
<code>release_date</code>: Release date in various string formats
</li>
<li>
<code>genres</code>: List of genres stored as a string (e.g., <code>"['Drama', 'Comedy']"</code>)
</li>
<li>
<code>duration</code>: Runtime as a string (e.g., <code>"2h 10m"</code>)
</li>
<li>
<code>rating</code>: IMDb rating (1–10)
</li>
<li>
<code>votes</code>: Number of votes as abbreviated strings (e.g., <code>"1.2M"</code>, <code>"500K"</code>)
</li>
<li>
<code>budget</code>: Budget with currency symbols and formatting (e.g., <code>"<span class="math inline">50,000,000&amp;quot;&lt;/code&gt;)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;gross_worldwide&lt;/code&gt;: Worldwide gross revenue with similar formatting&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;countries_origin&lt;/code&gt;: List of production countries as a string&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;
&lt;section id=&quot;cleaned-data&quot; class=&quot;level3&quot; data-number=&quot;2.2.2&quot;&gt;
&lt;h3 data-number=&quot;2.2.2&quot; class=&quot;anchored&quot; data-anchor-id=&quot;cleaned-data&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;header-section-number&quot;&gt;2.2.2&lt;/span&gt; Cleaned Data&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;After cleaning and filtering for the 1990–2025 period, our final dataset provides a comprehensive view of the modern film industry.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Number of observations&lt;/strong&gt;: 21869 rows&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Number of variables&lt;/strong&gt;: 23 columns&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Time period&lt;/strong&gt;: 1990 to 2025&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Geographic coverage&lt;/strong&gt;: Global, with a noted bias towards Western/Hollywood films.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Key variables&lt;/strong&gt;:
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;title&lt;/code&gt;: Name of the movie&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;release_date&lt;/code&gt;: Calendar date&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;primary_genre&lt;/code&gt;: Main genre of the film&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;duration_minutes&lt;/code&gt;: Numeric duration&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;rating&lt;/code&gt;: IMDb rating (1–10)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;votes_numeric&lt;/code&gt;: Number of audience votes&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;budget&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;gross_worldwide&lt;/code&gt;: Financial indicators&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;countries_origin&lt;/code&gt;: Countries involved in production&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;These variables allow us to study cultural (genre, country), economic (budget, gross), and qualitative (rating) aspects of the film industry.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;
&lt;section id=&quot;wrangling&quot; class=&quot;level2&quot; data-number=&quot;2.3&quot;&gt;
&lt;h2 data-number=&quot;2.3&quot; class=&quot;anchored&quot; data-anchor-id=&quot;wrangling&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;header-section-number&quot;&gt;2.3&lt;/span&gt; Wrangling&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;section id=&quot;general-transformations&quot; class=&quot;level3&quot; data-number=&quot;2.3.1&quot;&gt;
&lt;h3 data-number=&quot;2.3.1&quot; class=&quot;anchored&quot; data-anchor-id=&quot;general-transformations&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;header-section-number&quot;&gt;2.3.1&lt;/span&gt; General Transformations&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A separate Python script (&lt;code&gt;src/clean_data.py&lt;/code&gt;) was used to perform all data preprocessing. This approach keeps our reporting document clean and ensures reproducibility. The key steps performed were:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol type=&quot;1&quot;&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Filtering by Year&lt;/strong&gt;: The dataset was filtered to include only movies released between 1990 and 2025 to align with our research scope.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Duration Conversion&lt;/strong&gt;: The &lt;code&gt;duration&lt;/code&gt; column (e.g., “2h 10m”) was converted into a numerical format in a new &lt;code&gt;duration_minutes&lt;/code&gt; column.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Currency Cleaning&lt;/strong&gt;: Financial columns (&lt;code&gt;budget&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;gross_worldwide&lt;/code&gt;, etc.) were standardized into a numeric format by removing currency symbols and commas. All currencies were already in USD, so no conversion was needed.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Genre Extraction&lt;/strong&gt;: A &lt;code&gt;primary_genre&lt;/code&gt; column was created by extracting the first genre from the &lt;code&gt;genres&lt;/code&gt; list for each movie, simplifying classification. But also calculated genre weights in Q1 for multi-genre films to ensure accurate representation in the EDA.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Votes Normalization&lt;/strong&gt;: The &lt;code&gt;votes&lt;/code&gt; column was converted to a numeric type (&lt;code&gt;votes_numeric&lt;/code&gt;), handling abbreviated values (e.g., ‘K’ for thousands, ‘M’ for millions).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Date Conversion&lt;/strong&gt;: The &lt;code&gt;release_date&lt;/code&gt; column was converted to a proper datetime format.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;
&lt;section id=&quot;spotting-mistakes-and-missing-data&quot; class=&quot;level3&quot; data-number=&quot;2.3.2&quot;&gt;
&lt;h3 data-number=&quot;2.3.2&quot; class=&quot;anchored&quot; data-anchor-id=&quot;spotting-mistakes-and-missing-data&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;header-section-number&quot;&gt;2.3.2&lt;/span&gt; Spotting Mistakes and Missing Data&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;During preprocessing, several data quality issues were identified and addressed:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Missing Values&lt;/strong&gt;: Many older or less popular films had missing financial data (e.g., &lt;code&gt;budget&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;gross_worldwide&lt;/code&gt;). Instead of removing these rows, the missing values were kept as &lt;code&gt;NaN&lt;/code&gt; (Not a Number). This allows us to use the rows for non-financial analysis (like genre or duration trends) while excluding them from financial calculations where necessary.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Inconsistent Formatting&lt;/strong&gt;: As mentioned, &lt;code&gt;duration&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;budget&lt;/code&gt;, and &lt;code&gt;genres&lt;/code&gt; were not in a ready-to-use format. Our script standardized these to ensure they could be used in calculations and analysis.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Geographical Bias&lt;/strong&gt;: The dataset has a strong bias towards Hollywood and Western cinema. While we cannot “fix” this, we acknowledge this limitation in our analysis. Our findings on “global” trends will be interpreted with this bias in mind.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Inflation&lt;/strong&gt;: Financial data like &lt;code&gt;budget&lt;/code&gt; and &lt;code&gt;gross_worldwide&lt;/code&gt; are not adjusted for inflation. Direct comparisons of monetary values across different decades should be made with caution. That’s why for Q2 in the EDA chapter, we adjusted for inflation in order to have the real evolution of the film’s budgets.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Subjective Ratings&lt;/strong&gt;: IMDb scores are user-based and can reflect cultural or regional bias.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;
&lt;section id=&quot;exploratory-data-analysis&quot; class=&quot;level1&quot; data-number=&quot;3&quot;&gt;
&lt;h1 data-number=&quot;3&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;header-section-number&quot;&gt;3&lt;/span&gt; Exploratory Data Analysis&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In this section, we conduct an exploratory data analysis (EDA) to answer our research sub-questions. Each sub-section addresses one question, providing visualizations and interpretations to uncover patterns in the global film industry from 1990 to 2025.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;section id=&quot;q1-which-film-genres-have-dominated-each-decade&quot; class=&quot;level2&quot; data-number=&quot;3.1&quot;&gt;
