<p>
<strong>Interpretation:</strong>
</p>
<p>
<a href="#fig-budget-evolution" class="quarto-xref">Figure 2</a> reveals a surprising divergence between nominal spending and real purchasing power. While the nominal budget (purple line) suggests a gradual increase from roughly $11 million in 1990 to peaks of $30 million in recent years, the inflation-adjusted “Real Budget” (gold line, Base 2025) tells a starkly different story. Contrary to the expectation that costs have skyrocketed, the regression line indicates a clear downward trend in real median budgets over the 35-year period.
</p>
<p>
In real terms (2025 dollars), median budgets actually peaked in the late 1990s, reaching highs of over $35 million. Since then, despite significant volatility, the purchasing power allocated to the median film has steadily eroded, dropping to approximately $19 million by 2025.
</p>
<p>
Several factors may explain this real-term decline. First, the democratization of digital filmmaking tools may have lowered the barrier to entry, allowing more low-to-mid-budget films to be produced more cheaply. Second, the industry may be experiencing a “hollowing out” effect: while massive blockbusters (not captured by the median) have ballooned in cost, the “middle-class” movie has faced tightening budget constraints.
</p>
<p>
The graph also highlights distinct periods of volatility. A sharp dip is visible around the 2008 financial crisis and again in the mid-2010s. Interestingly, while there was a significant spike in real spending around 2022–2023 (likely a post-pandemic production surge) values have since corrected downward. Overall, the analysis overturns the assumption that filmmaking is becoming universally more expensive; instead, it suggests that outside of mega-blockbusters, the typical film is being made with a leaner real-world budget than it was three decades ago.
</p>
</section>
<section id="q3-to-what-extent-does-financial-investment-budget-influence-audience-reception-imdb-rating" class="level2" data-number="3.3">
<h2 data-number="3.3" class="anchored" data-anchor-id="q3-to-what-extent-does-financial-investment-budget-influence-audience-reception-imdb-rating">
<span class="header-section-number">3.3</span> Q3: To what extent does financial investment (budget) influence audience reception (IMDb rating)?
</h2>
<p>
A central question for any film producer is whether more money leads to a better movie. We investigate this by plotting <strong>inflation-adjusted budgets</strong> against their IMDb ratings. Given that budgets span several orders of magnitude, we use a logarithmic scale for the budget axis to better visualize the relationship.
</p>
