<p>
<strong>Interpretation:</strong>
</p>
<p>
<a href="#fig-budget-rating-correlation" class="quarto-xref">Figure 3</a> demonstrates that there is an extremely weak relationship between a film’s inflation-adjusted budget and its IMDb rating. While the regression curve (red line) shows a slight upward inflection at the highest budget levels, the overall pattern is largely flat. This visual observation is confirmed by the low Pearson correlation coefficient of 0.140, indicating only a minimal linear association between financial investment and audience reception.
</p>
<p>
The dispersion of points across the logarithmic budget scale further supports this conclusion. Highly rated films (with scores above 7 or 8) appear across the entire financial spectrum, ranging from micro-budget productions costing less than $10,000 (roughly <span class="math inline">10^4</span>) to massive blockbusters exceeding $200–300 million. Likewise, low-rated films are distributed widely. This significant vertical spread suggests that audience appreciation depends far more on qualitative factors (such as storytelling, acting, and originality) than on the magnitude of resources spent.
</p>
<p>
However, a subtle pattern emerges at the extreme right of the plot: films with the highest inflation-adjusted budgets (approaching <span class="math inline">10^8</span> and above) tend to avoid the lowest rating range (scores below 4). In other words, while spending massive amounts does not guarantee a masterpiece, it appears to reduce the likelihood of a film being critically panned. This “floor effect” likely results from the extensive professional oversight, technical standards, and production value inherent in large-scale studio projects.
</p>
<p>
Overall, this analysis confirms that larger budgets do not strictly correlate with higher ratings. The data highlights the critical success of numerous low-to-mid-budget films, proving that creativity can rival visual spectacle. For producers, this emphasizes that while money can ensure technical competence, it cannot buy audience satisfaction.
</p>
</section>
<section id="q3a-is-there-a-correlation-between-a-films-budget-and-its-box-office-revenue" class="level2" data-number="3.4">
<h2 data-number="3.4" class="anchored" data-anchor-id="q3a-is-there-a-correlation-between-a-films-budget-and-its-box-office-revenue">
<span class="header-section-number">3.4</span> Q3a: Is there a correlation between a film’s budget and its box office revenue?
</h2>
<p>
While budget may not predict audience ratings, it might be a better predictor of commercial success. We now examine the relationship between a film’s <strong>inflation-adjusted budget</strong> and its <strong>inflation-adjusted worldwide gross revenue</strong>. This analysis helps determine whether higher investments typically yield higher financial returns.
</p>
<div id="cell-fig-budget-revenue-correlation" class="cell" data-execution_count="5">
