<span id="cb10-37"><a href="#cb10-37" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu"># Introduction</span></span>
<span id="cb10-38"><a href="#cb10-38" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-39"><a href="#cb10-39" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">## Overview &amp; Motivation</span></span>
<span id="cb10-40"><a href="#cb10-40" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>Over the last few decades, the film industry has undergone major transformations, shaped by globalization, technological innovation and changing audience preferences. As students who grew up watching movies and series from many genres and countries, we have personally experienced these changes. This makes the topic not only interesting but also culturally relevant and close to us. Studying the evolution of cinema through data allows us to understand how entertainment reflects societal changes, technological progress, and shifting audience tastes. It is a topic that meaningfully connects culture, society, and data science.</span>
<span id="cb10-41"><a href="#cb10-41" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-42"><a href="#cb10-42" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">## Project Goals</span></span>
<span id="cb10-43"><a href="#cb10-43" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>The goal of this project is to analyze the evolution of the global film industry from 1990 to 2025. We focused on this specific timeframe to ensure data consistency and completeness, as financial records prior to 1990 are often fragmented, and to specifically capture the modern era defined by the digital revolution and the globalization of film markets. We aim to understand how public tastes and film characteristics such as, genre, budget, duration, and country of origin, have changed over time. This topic is relevant as it connects art, culture, and data science, allowing us to use data to explore historical and cultural trends in entertainment. By transforming creative aspects of cinema into measurable patterns, we can gain insights into how technology, audience preferences, and globalization have shaped the movies we watch today. The analysis will focus on exploratory data analysis (EDA) to identify major trends and correlations.</span>
<span id="cb10-44"><a href="#cb10-44" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-45"><a href="#cb10-45" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">## Related Work</span></span>
<span id="cb10-46"><a href="#cb10-46" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>Our project was inspired by several online analyses and discussions. For example, IMDb and Kaggle host many studies that explore genre evolution, variations in movie ratings over time, and Hollywood budget inflation. Academic discussions about the globalisation of cinema also highlight the growing impact of film industries such as Bollywood, Nollywood and East Asian cinema. Drawing on these references, we were able to structure our questions and identify the most relevant variables for understanding how the industry has progressed, such as genre, ratings, budgets and countries.</span>
<span id="cb10-47"><a href="#cb10-47" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-48"><a href="#cb10-48" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">## Research Questions</span></span>
<span id="cb10-49"><a href="#cb10-49" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>Our primary research question is:</span>
<span id="cb10-50"><a href="#cb10-50" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">- </span>How do public tastes and movie characteristics (such as genres, budgets, durations, and origins) vary across time in the global film industry between 1990 and 2025?</span>
<span id="cb10-51"><a href="#cb10-51" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-52"><a href="#cb10-52" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>To address this, we will investigate the following sub-questions, each providing a different lens through which to view the industry&#39;s evolution:</span>
<span id="cb10-53"><a href="#cb10-53" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-54"><a href="#cb10-54" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Which film genres dominated each decade?** This question helps us understand changing cultural tastes and identify which storytelling formats were most popular in different eras.</span>
<span id="cb10-55"><a href="#cb10-55" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**How have movie budgets evolved over time?** Analyzing budget trends reveals the economic shifts in the film industry, from the rise of blockbusters to the impact of new technologies.</span>
<span id="cb10-56"><a href="#cb10-56" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**To what extent does financial investment (budget) influence audience reception (IMDb rating)?** This explores whether higher financial investment typically translates into better audience reception, a key consideration for producers.</span>
<span id="cb10-57"><a href="#cb10-57" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Is there a correlation between a film&#39;s budget and its box office revenue?** This explores whether higher financial investment typically translates into better revenue, another key consideration for producers.</span>
<span id="cb10-58"><a href="#cb10-58" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**How has the typical duration of feature films evolved over the last three decades?** The answer to this question can reflect changes in storytelling norms and audience viewing habits.</span>
<span id="cb10-59"><a href="#cb10-59" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Which countries have dominated global film production over different periods?** This highlights the geographical shifts in filmmaking, showing the influence of globalization and the rise of new markets.</span>
<span id="cb10-60"><a href="#cb10-60" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Do the highest-rated films consistently come from the same regions?** This question examines whether critical acclaim is concentrated in specific cultural or geographical areas.</span>
<span id="cb10-61"><a href="#cb10-61" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-62"><a href="#cb10-62" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu"># Data</span></span>
<span id="cb10-63"><a href="#cb10-63" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-64"><a href="#cb10-64" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">## Sources</span></span>
<span id="cb10-65"><a href="#cb10-65" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>Our primary dataset was sourced from Kaggle: **IMDb Movies from 1920 to 2025**, published by Raed Addala. The data was accessed in November 2025. The dataset in CSV format is available at the following URL: <span class="co">[</span><span class="ot">https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/raedaddala/imdb-movies-from-1960-to-2023/data</span><span class="co">](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/raedaddala/imdb-movies-from-1960-to-2023/data)</span>.</span>
<span id="cb10-66"><a href="#cb10-66" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-67"><a href="#cb10-67" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">## Description</span></span>
<span id="cb10-68"><a href="#cb10-68" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-69"><a href="#cb10-69" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">### Raw Data</span></span>
<span id="cb10-70"><a href="#cb10-70" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>The original dataset obtained from Kaggle contains:</span>
<span id="cb10-71"><a href="#cb10-71" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-72"><a href="#cb10-72" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">- </span>**Number of observations**: ~60,000 movies</span>
<span id="cb10-73"><a href="#cb10-73" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">- </span>**Number of variables**: 23 columns</span>
<span id="cb10-74"><a href="#cb10-74" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">- </span>**Time period**: 1920 to 2025</span>
<span id="cb10-75"><a href="#cb10-75" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">- </span>**Format**: CSV file</span>
<span id="cb10-76"><a href="#cb10-76" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">- </span>**Raw variables include**:</span>
<span id="cb10-77"><a href="#cb10-77" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">    -   </span><span class="in">`title`</span>: Movie title as a string</span>
<span id="cb10-78"><a href="#cb10-78" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">    -   </span><span class="in">`release_date`</span>: Release date in various string formats</span>
<span id="cb10-79"><a href="#cb10-79" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">    -   </span><span class="in">`genres`</span>: List of genres stored as a string (e.g., <span class="in">`&quot;[&#39;Drama&#39;, &#39;Comedy&#39;]&quot;`</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-80"><a href="#cb10-80" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">    -   </span><span class="in">`duration`</span>: Runtime as a string (e.g., <span class="in">`&quot;2h 10m&quot;`</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-81"><a href="#cb10-81" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">    -   </span><span class="in">`rating`</span>: IMDb rating (1–10)</span>
<span id="cb10-82"><a href="#cb10-82" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">    -   </span><span class="in">`votes`</span>: Number of votes as abbreviated strings (e.g., <span class="in">`&quot;1.2M&quot;`</span>, <span class="in">`&quot;500K&quot;`</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-83"><a href="#cb10-83" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">    -   </span><span class="in">`budget`</span>: Budget with currency symbols and formatting (e.g., <span class="in">`&quot;$50,000,000&quot;`</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-84"><a href="#cb10-84" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">    -   </span><span class="in">`gross_worldwide`</span>: Worldwide gross revenue with similar formatting</span>
<span id="cb10-85"><a href="#cb10-85" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">    -   </span><span class="in">`countries_origin`</span>: List of production countries as a string</span>
<span id="cb10-86"><a href="#cb10-86" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-87"><a href="#cb10-87" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">### Cleaned Data</span></span>
<span id="cb10-88"><a href="#cb10-88" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>After cleaning and filtering for the 1990–2025 period, our final dataset provides a comprehensive view of the modern film industry.</span>
<span id="cb10-89"><a href="#cb10-89" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-90"><a href="#cb10-90" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">- </span>**Number of observations**: 21869 rows</span>
<span id="cb10-91"><a href="#cb10-91" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">- </span>**Number of variables**: 23 columns</span>
<span id="cb10-92"><a href="#cb10-92" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">- </span>**Time period**: 1990 to 2025</span>
<span id="cb10-93"><a href="#cb10-93" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">- </span>**Geographic coverage**: Global, with a noted bias towards Western/Hollywood films.</span>
<span id="cb10-94"><a href="#cb10-94" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">- </span>**Key variables**:</span>
<span id="cb10-95"><a href="#cb10-95" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">    -   </span><span class="in">`title`</span>: Name of the movie</span>
<span id="cb10-96"><a href="#cb10-96" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">    -   </span><span class="in">`release_date`</span>: Calendar date</span>
<span id="cb10-97"><a href="#cb10-97" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">    -   </span><span class="in">`primary_genre`</span>: Main genre of the film</span>
<span id="cb10-98"><a href="#cb10-98" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">    -   </span><span class="in">`duration_minutes`</span>: Numeric duration</span>
<span id="cb10-99"><a href="#cb10-99" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">    -   </span><span class="in">`rating`</span>: IMDb rating (1–10)</span>
<span id="cb10-100"><a href="#cb10-100" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">    -   </span><span class="in">`votes_numeric`</span>: Number of audience votes</span>
<span id="cb10-101"><a href="#cb10-101" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">    -   </span><span class="in">`budget`</span>, <span class="in">`gross_worldwide`</span>: Financial indicators</span>
<span id="cb10-102"><a href="#cb10-102" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">    -   </span><span class="in">`countries_origin`</span>: Countries involved in production</span>
<span id="cb10-103"><a href="#cb10-103" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-104"><a href="#cb10-104" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>These variables allow us to study cultural (genre, country), economic (budget, gross), and qualitative (rating) aspects of the film industry.</span>
<span id="cb10-105"><a href="#cb10-105" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-106"><a href="#cb10-106" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">## Wrangling</span></span>
<span id="cb10-107"><a href="#cb10-107" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-108"><a href="#cb10-108" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">### General Transformations</span></span>
<span id="cb10-109"><a href="#cb10-109" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>A separate Python script (<span class="in">`src/clean_data.py`</span>) was used to perform all data preprocessing. This approach keeps our reporting document clean and ensures reproducibility. The key steps performed were:</span>
<span id="cb10-110"><a href="#cb10-110" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-111"><a href="#cb10-111" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">1.  </span>**Filtering by Year**: The dataset was filtered to include only movies released between 1990 and 2025 to align with our research scope.</span>
<span id="cb10-112"><a href="#cb10-112" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">2.  </span>**Duration Conversion**: The <span class="in">`duration`</span> column (e.g., &quot;2h 10m&quot;) was converted into a numerical format in a new <span class="in">`duration_minutes`</span> column.</span>
<span id="cb10-113"><a href="#cb10-113" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">3.  </span>**Currency Cleaning**: Financial columns (<span class="in">`budget`</span>, <span class="in">`gross_worldwide`</span>, etc.) were standardized into a numeric format by removing currency symbols and commas. All currencies were already in USD, so no conversion was needed.</span>
<span id="cb10-114"><a href="#cb10-114" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">4.  </span>**Genre Extraction**: A <span class="in">`primary_genre`</span> column was created by extracting the first genre from the <span class="in">`genres`</span> list for each movie, simplifying classification. But also calculated genre weights in Q1 for multi-genre films to ensure accurate representation in the EDA.</span>
<span id="cb10-115"><a href="#cb10-115" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">5.  </span>**Votes Normalization**: The <span class="in">`votes`</span> column was converted to a numeric type (<span class="in">`votes_numeric`</span>), handling abbreviated values (e.g., &#39;K&#39; for thousands, &#39;M&#39; for millions).</span>
<span id="cb10-116"><a href="#cb10-116" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">6.  </span>**Date Conversion**: The <span class="in">`release_date`</span> column was converted to a proper datetime format.</span>
<span id="cb10-117"><a href="#cb10-117" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-118"><a href="#cb10-118" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">### Spotting Mistakes and Missing Data</span></span>
<span id="cb10-119"><a href="#cb10-119" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>During preprocessing, several data quality issues were identified and addressed:</span>
<span id="cb10-120"><a href="#cb10-120" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-121"><a href="#cb10-121" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Missing Values**: Many older or less popular films had missing financial data (e.g., <span class="in">`budget`</span>, <span class="in">`gross_worldwide`</span>). Instead of removing these rows, the missing values were kept as <span class="in">`NaN`</span> (Not a Number). This allows us to use the rows for non-financial analysis (like genre or duration trends) while excluding them from financial calculations where necessary.</span>
<span id="cb10-122"><a href="#cb10-122" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Inconsistent Formatting**: As mentioned, <span class="in">`duration`</span>, <span class="in">`budget`</span>, and <span class="in">`genres`</span> were not in a ready-to-use format. Our script standardized these to ensure they could be used in calculations and analysis.</span>
<span id="cb10-123"><a href="#cb10-123" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Geographical Bias**: The dataset has a strong bias towards Hollywood and Western cinema. While we cannot &quot;fix&quot; this, we acknowledge this limitation in our analysis. Our findings on &quot;global&quot; trends will be interpreted with this bias in mind.</span>
<span id="cb10-124"><a href="#cb10-124" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Inflation**: Financial data like <span class="in">`budget`</span> and <span class="in">`gross_worldwide`</span> are not adjusted for inflation. Direct comparisons of monetary values across different decades should be made with caution. That&#39;s why for Q2 in the EDA chapter, we adjusted for inflation in order to have the real evolution of the film&#39;s budgets.</span>
<span id="cb10-125"><a href="#cb10-125" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">-   </span>**Subjective Ratings**: IMDb scores are user-based and can reflect cultural or regional bias.</span>
<span id="cb10-126"><a href="#cb10-126" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-127"><a href="#cb10-127" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu"># Exploratory Data Analysis</span></span>
<span id="cb10-128"><a href="#cb10-128" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-129"><a href="#cb10-129" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>In this section, we conduct an exploratory data analysis (EDA) to answer our research sub-questions. Each sub-section addresses one question, providing visualizations and interpretations to uncover patterns in the global film industry from 1990 to 2025.</span>
<span id="cb10-130"><a href="#cb10-130" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-133"><a href="#cb10-133" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="in">```{python}</span></span>
<span id="cb10-134"><a href="#cb10-134" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#| label: setup-eda</span></span>
<span id="cb10-135"><a href="#cb10-135" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#| include: false</span></span>
<span id="cb10-136"><a href="#cb10-136" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-137"><a href="#cb10-137" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="im">import</span> pandas <span class="im">as</span> pd</span>
<span id="cb10-138"><a href="#cb10-138" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="im">import</span> numpy <span class="im">as</span> np</span>
<span id="cb10-139"><a href="#cb10-139" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="im">import</span> matplotlib.pyplot <span class="im">as</span> plt</span>
<span id="cb10-140"><a href="#cb10-140" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="im">import</span> seaborn <span class="im">as</span> sns</span>
<span id="cb10-141"><a href="#cb10-141" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="im">import</span> ast</span>
<span id="cb10-142"><a href="#cb10-142" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="im">from</span> pathlib <span class="im">import</span> Path</span>
<span id="cb10-143"><a href="#cb10-143" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-144"><a href="#cb10-144" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Set publication-quality style for all plots</span></span>
<span id="cb10-145"><a href="#cb10-145" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>sns.set_theme(style<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&quot;whitegrid&quot;</span>, context<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&quot;notebook&quot;</span>, </span>
<span id="cb10-146"><a href="#cb10-146" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>              palette<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&quot;colorblind&quot;</span>, font_scale<span class="op">=</span><span class="fl">1.1</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-147"><a href="#cb10-147" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-148"><a href="#cb10-148" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Define project root assuming a standard structure</span></span>
<span id="cb10-149"><a href="#cb10-149" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># This makes the notebook more portable</span></span>
<span id="cb10-150"><a href="#cb10-150" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>project_root <span class="op">=</span> Path.cwd().parent.parent</span>
<span id="cb10-151"><a href="#cb10-151" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>processed_data_path <span class="op">=</span> project_root <span class="op">/</span> <span class="st">&quot;dsas_template&quot;</span> <span class="op">/</span> <span class="st">&quot;data&quot;</span> <span class="op">/</span> <span class="st">&quot;processed&quot;</span> <span class="op">/</span> <span class="st">&quot;Movie_Data_1920_to_2025_cleaned.csv&quot;</span></span>
<span id="cb10-152"><a href="#cb10-152" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data <span class="op">=</span> pd.read_csv(processed_data_path, skipinitialspace<span class="op">=</span><span class="va">True</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-153"><a href="#cb10-153" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-154"><a href="#cb10-154" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Convert release_date to datetime objects</span></span>
<span id="cb10-155"><a href="#cb10-155" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data[<span class="st">&#39;release_date&#39;</span>] <span class="op">=</span> pd.to_datetime(data[<span class="st">&#39;release_date&#39;</span>])</span>
<span id="cb10-156"><a href="#cb10-156" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-157"><a href="#cb10-157" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Create a &#39;decade&#39; column for analysis</span></span>
<span id="cb10-158"><a href="#cb10-158" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data[<span class="st">&#39;decade&#39;</span>] <span class="op">=</span> (data[<span class="st">&#39;release_date&#39;</span>].dt.year <span class="op">//</span> <span class="dv">10</span>) <span class="op">*</span> <span class="dv">10</span></span>
<span id="cb10-159"><a href="#cb10-159" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="in">```</span></span>
<span id="cb10-160"><a href="#cb10-160" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-161"><a href="#cb10-161" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">## Q1: Which film genres have dominated each decade?</span></span>
<span id="cb10-162"><a href="#cb10-162" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-163"><a href="#cb10-163" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>To understand shifting cultural tastes, we first analyze the prevalence of different film genres over time. We group movies by decade (1990s, 2000s, 2010s, 2020s) and their weighted genre to identify which categories were most produced. @fig-genre-trends shows the relative percentage of each of the five most common genres in each decade.</span>
<span id="cb10-164"><a href="#cb10-164" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-167"><a href="#cb10-167" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="in">```{python}</span></span>
<span id="cb10-168"><a href="#cb10-168" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#| label: fig-genre-trends</span></span>
<span id="cb10-169"><a href="#cb10-169" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#| fig-cap: &quot;Proportion of top 5 film genres for each decade from 1990 to 2020s&quot;</span></span>
<span id="cb10-170"><a href="#cb10-170" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-171"><a href="#cb10-171" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Load the original data to access the &#39;genres&#39; column</span></span>
<span id="cb10-172"><a href="#cb10-172" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>original_data_path <span class="op">=</span> project_root <span class="op">/</span> <span class="st">&quot;dsas_template&quot;</span> <span class="op">/</span> <span class="st">&quot;data&quot;</span> <span class="op">/</span> <span class="st">&quot;raw&quot;</span> <span class="op">/</span> <span class="st">&quot;Movie_Data_1920_to_2025.csv&quot;</span></span>
<span id="cb10-173"><a href="#cb10-173" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data_q1 <span class="op">=</span> pd.read_csv(original_data_path, skipinitialspace<span class="op">=</span><span class="va">True</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-174"><a href="#cb10-174" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-175"><a href="#cb10-175" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Perform necessary cleaning steps for this analysis</span></span>
<span id="cb10-176"><a href="#cb10-176" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data_q1[<span class="st">&#39;release_date&#39;</span>] <span class="op">=</span> pd.to_datetime(data_q1[<span class="st">&#39;release_date&#39;</span>], errors<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;coerce&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-177"><a href="#cb10-177" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data_q1.dropna(subset<span class="op">=</span>[<span class="st">&#39;release_date&#39;</span>], inplace<span class="op">=</span><span class="va">True</span>) <span class="co"># Drop rows where date conversion failed</span></span>
<span id="cb10-178"><a href="#cb10-178" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data_q1[<span class="st">&#39;decade&#39;</span>] <span class="op">=</span> (data_q1[<span class="st">&#39;release_date&#39;</span>].dt.year <span class="op">//</span> <span class="dv">10</span>) <span class="op">*</span> <span class="dv">10</span></span>
<span id="cb10-179"><a href="#cb10-179" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data_q1 <span class="op">=</span> data_q1[data_q1[<span class="st">&#39;decade&#39;</span>] <span class="op">&gt;=</span> <span class="dv">1990</span>] <span class="co"># Filter for the correct time period</span></span>
<span id="cb10-180"><a href="#cb10-180" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-181"><a href="#cb10-181" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Safely evaluate the &#39;genres&#39; string into a list</span></span>
<span id="cb10-182"><a href="#cb10-182" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data_q1[<span class="st">&#39;genres_list&#39;</span>] <span class="op">=</span> data_q1[<span class="st">&#39;genres&#39;</span>].<span class="bu">apply</span>(<span class="kw">lambda</span> x: ast.literal_eval(x) <span class="cf">if</span> <span class="bu">isinstance</span>(x, <span class="bu">str</span>) <span class="kw">and</span> x.startswith(<span class="st">&#39;[&#39;</span>) <span class="cf">else</span> [])</span>
<span id="cb10-183"><a href="#cb10-183" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-184"><a href="#cb10-184" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Calculate weight for each genre (1 / number of genres)</span></span>
<span id="cb10-185"><a href="#cb10-185" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data_q1[<span class="st">&#39;genre_weight&#39;</span>] <span class="op">=</span> data_q1[<span class="st">&#39;genres_list&#39;</span>].<span class="bu">apply</span>(<span class="kw">lambda</span> x: <span class="dv">1</span><span class="op">/</span><span class="bu">len</span>(x) <span class="cf">if</span> <span class="bu">len</span>(x) <span class="op">&gt;</span> <span class="dv">0</span> <span class="cf">else</span> <span class="dv">0</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-186"><a href="#cb10-186" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-187"><a href="#cb10-187" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Explode the DataFrame to have one row per genre for each movie</span></span>
<span id="cb10-188"><a href="#cb10-188" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>genre_data <span class="op">=</span> data_q1.explode(<span class="st">&#39;genres_list&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-189"><a href="#cb10-189" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>genre_data <span class="op">=</span> genre_data.rename(columns<span class="op">=</span>{<span class="st">&#39;genres_list&#39;</span>: <span class="st">&#39;genre&#39;</span>})</span>
<span id="cb10-190"><a href="#cb10-190" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-191"><a href="#cb10-191" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Calculate total movies per decade (for proportion calculation)</span></span>
<span id="cb10-192"><a href="#cb10-192" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>decade_totals <span class="op">=</span> data_q1.groupby(<span class="st">&#39;decade&#39;</span>).size().reset_index(name<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;total_count&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-193"><a href="#cb10-193" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-194"><a href="#cb10-194" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Calculate weighted count of each genre per decade</span></span>
<span id="cb10-195"><a href="#cb10-195" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>genre_counts <span class="op">=</span> genre_data.groupby([<span class="st">&#39;decade&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;genre&#39;</span>])[<span class="st">&#39;genre_weight&#39;</span>].<span class="bu">sum</span>().reset_index(name<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;count&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-196"><a href="#cb10-196" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-197"><a href="#cb10-197" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Merge to get total counts and calculate proportion</span></span>
<span id="cb10-198"><a href="#cb10-198" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>genre_counts <span class="op">=</span> pd.merge(genre_counts, decade_totals, on<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;decade&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-199"><a href="#cb10-199" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>genre_counts[<span class="st">&#39;proportion&#39;</span>] <span class="op">=</span> genre_counts[<span class="st">&#39;count&#39;</span>] <span class="op">/</span> genre_counts[<span class="st">&#39;total_count&#39;</span>]</span>
<span id="cb10-200"><a href="#cb10-200" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-201"><a href="#cb10-201" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Get the top 5 genres per decade based on proportion</span></span>
<span id="cb10-202"><a href="#cb10-202" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>top_genres_per_decade <span class="op">=</span> (</span>
<span id="cb10-203"><a href="#cb10-203" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    genre_counts.groupby(<span class="st">&#39;decade&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-204"><a href="#cb10-204" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    .<span class="bu">apply</span>(<span class="kw">lambda</span> x: x.nlargest(<span class="dv">5</span>, <span class="st">&#39;proportion&#39;</span>))</span>
<span id="cb10-205"><a href="#cb10-205" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    .reset_index(drop<span class="op">=</span><span class="va">True</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-206"><a href="#cb10-206" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>)</span>
<span id="cb10-207"><a href="#cb10-207" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-208"><a href="#cb10-208" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Create the plot</span></span>
<span id="cb10-209"><a href="#cb10-209" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>fig, ax <span class="op">=</span> plt.subplots(figsize<span class="op">=</span>(<span class="fl">8.25</span>, <span class="fl">5.25</span>))</span>
<span id="cb10-210"><a href="#cb10-210" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-211"><a href="#cb10-211" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>sns.barplot(data<span class="op">=</span>top_genres_per_decade, x<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;decade&#39;</span>, y<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;proportion&#39;</span>, hue<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;genre&#39;</span>, ax<span class="op">=</span>ax)</span>
<span id="cb10-212"><a href="#cb10-212" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-213"><a href="#cb10-213" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Add film count annotations on the x-axis</span></span>
<span id="cb10-214"><a href="#cb10-214" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>decade_counts_dict <span class="op">=</span> decade_totals.set_index(<span class="st">&#39;decade&#39;</span>)[<span class="st">&#39;total_count&#39;</span>].to_dict()</span>
<span id="cb10-215"><a href="#cb10-215" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>x_labels <span class="op">=</span> [<span class="ss">f&quot;</span><span class="sc">{</span><span class="bu">int</span>(decade)<span class="sc">}</span><span class="ss">s</span><span class="ch">\n</span><span class="ss">(n=</span><span class="sc">{</span>decade_counts_dict<span class="sc">.</span>get(decade, <span class="dv">0</span>)<span class="sc">:,}</span><span class="ss">)&quot;</span> </span>
<span id="cb10-216"><a href="#cb10-216" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>            <span class="cf">for</span> decade <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="bu">sorted</span>(decade_totals[<span class="st">&#39;decade&#39;</span>].unique())]</span>
<span id="cb10-217"><a href="#cb10-217" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_xticklabels(x_labels)</span>
<span id="cb10-218"><a href="#cb10-218" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-219"><a href="#cb10-219" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Customize plot</span></span>
<span id="cb10-220"><a href="#cb10-220" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_title(<span class="st">&quot;Proportion of Dominant Film Genres by Decade&quot;</span>, </span>
<span id="cb10-221"><a href="#cb10-221" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>             fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">16</span>, fontweight<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;bold&#39;</span>, pad<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">15</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-222"><a href="#cb10-222" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_xlabel(<span class="st">&quot;Decade (n = number of films)&quot;</span>, fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">12</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-223"><a href="#cb10-223" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_ylabel(<span class="st">&quot;Proportion of Movies Produced&quot;</span>, fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">12</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-224"><a href="#cb10-224" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.legend(title<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;Genre&#39;</span>, bbox_to_anchor<span class="op">=</span>(<span class="fl">1.05</span>, <span class="dv">1</span>), loc<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;upper left&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-225"><a href="#cb10-225" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.grid(<span class="va">True</span>, axis<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;y&#39;</span>, alpha<span class="op">=</span><span class="fl">0.3</span>, linestyle<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;--&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-226"><a href="#cb10-226" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.yaxis.set_major_formatter(plt.FuncFormatter(<span class="kw">lambda</span> y, _: <span class="st">&#39;</span><span class="sc">{:.0%}</span><span class="st">&#39;</span>.<span class="bu">format</span>(y)))</span>
<span id="cb10-227"><a href="#cb10-227" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-228"><a href="#cb10-228" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>plt.tight_layout()</span>
<span id="cb10-229"><a href="#cb10-229" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>plt.show()</span>
<span id="cb10-230"><a href="#cb10-230" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="in">```</span></span>
<span id="cb10-231"><a href="#cb10-231" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-232"><a href="#cb10-232" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>**Interpretation:**</span>
<span id="cb10-233"><a href="#cb10-233" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-234"><a href="#cb10-234" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>Drama has consistently been the most dominant genre across all decades, representing roughly 20-25% of all films produced. Comedy also maintains a strong presence as the second most common genre for most of the timeline, though it experienced a decline from roughly 13% in the 1990s to roughly 10-11% in the 2010s and 2020s. This stability in the top two spots suggests a foundational audience interest in character-driven stories and light-hearted entertainment.</span>
<span id="cb10-235"><a href="#cb10-235" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-236"><a href="#cb10-236" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>However, the other genres demonstrate more significant shifts. For example, Action films were a top-five genre in the 1990s but dropped out of the top five in the 2000s and did not return in subsequent decades. The 2000s saw the emergence of Documentary as a top genre (replacing Action), while the 2010s marked the peak of Documentary films, where they accounted for over 10% of the mix.</span>
<span id="cb10-237"><a href="#cb10-237" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-238"><a href="#cb10-238" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>By the 2020s, the landscape shifted again: Horror emerged as a new top-five contender. Contrary to previous trends, Thriller has grown in prominence, approaching the popularity of Comedy, though Comedy retains the second position. Overall, the chart shows that while Drama remains the cultural constant, the secondary positions shift dynamically between Romance, Thriller, Documentary, and Horror in response to changing industry trends.</span>
<span id="cb10-239"><a href="#cb10-239" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-240"><a href="#cb10-240" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">## Q2: How have movie budgets evolved over time?</span></span>
<span id="cb10-241"><a href="#cb10-241" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-242"><a href="#cb10-242" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>To examine how the economics of filmmaking have changed, we analyze the median movie budget per year from 1990 to 2025. Using the median instead of the mean reduces the influence of extremely high-budget &quot;tentpole&quot; productions, allowing us to observe general industry trends more accurately. We also adjust for inflation.</span>
<span id="cb10-243"><a href="#cb10-243" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-244"><a href="#cb10-244" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>**Data Source for Inflation:** U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics (CPI-U).</span>
<span id="cb10-245"><a href="#cb10-245" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-248"><a href="#cb10-248" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="in">```{python}</span></span>
<span id="cb10-249"><a href="#cb10-249" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#| label: fig-budget-evolution</span></span>
<span id="cb10-250"><a href="#cb10-250" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#| fig-cap: &quot;Median movie production budget: Nominal vs. Inflation-Adjusted (Base 2025)&quot;</span></span>
<span id="cb10-251"><a href="#cb10-251" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-252"><a href="#cb10-252" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># CPI data (Consumer Price Index for All Urban Consumers) sourced from U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics</span></span>
<span id="cb10-253"><a href="#cb10-253" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Base year for adjustment: 2025 (using estimated CPI)</span></span>
<span id="cb10-254"><a href="#cb10-254" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>cpi_data <span class="op">=</span> {</span>
<span id="cb10-255"><a href="#cb10-255" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="dv">1990</span>: <span class="fl">130.7</span>, <span class="dv">1991</span>: <span class="fl">136.2</span>, <span class="dv">1992</span>: <span class="fl">140.3</span>, <span class="dv">1993</span>: <span class="fl">144.5</span>, <span class="dv">1994</span>: <span class="fl">148.2</span>,</span>
<span id="cb10-256"><a href="#cb10-256" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="dv">1995</span>: <span class="fl">152.4</span>, <span class="dv">1996</span>: <span class="fl">156.9</span>, <span class="dv">1997</span>: <span class="fl">160.5</span>, <span class="dv">1998</span>: <span class="fl">163.0</span>, <span class="dv">1999</span>: <span class="fl">166.6</span>,</span>
<span id="cb10-257"><a href="#cb10-257" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="dv">2000</span>: <span class="fl">172.2</span>, <span class="dv">2001</span>: <span class="fl">177.1</span>, <span class="dv">2002</span>: <span class="fl">179.9</span>, <span class="dv">2003</span>: <span class="fl">184.0</span>, <span class="dv">2004</span>: <span class="fl">188.9</span>,</span>
<span id="cb10-258"><a href="#cb10-258" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="dv">2005</span>: <span class="fl">195.3</span>, <span class="dv">2006</span>: <span class="fl">201.6</span>, <span class="dv">2007</span>: <span class="fl">207.3</span>, <span class="dv">2008</span>: <span class="fl">215.3</span>, <span class="dv">2009</span>: <span class="fl">214.5</span>,</span>
<span id="cb10-259"><a href="#cb10-259" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="dv">2010</span>: <span class="fl">218.1</span>, <span class="dv">2011</span>: <span class="fl">224.9</span>, <span class="dv">2012</span>: <span class="fl">229.6</span>, <span class="dv">2013</span>: <span class="fl">233.0</span>, <span class="dv">2014</span>: <span class="fl">236.7</span>,</span>
<span id="cb10-260"><a href="#cb10-260" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="dv">2015</span>: <span class="fl">237.0</span>, <span class="dv">2016</span>: <span class="fl">240.0</span>, <span class="dv">2017</span>: <span class="fl">245.1</span>, <span class="dv">2018</span>: <span class="fl">251.1</span>, <span class="dv">2019</span>: <span class="fl">255.7</span>,</span>
<span id="cb10-261"><a href="#cb10-261" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="dv">2020</span>: <span class="fl">258.8</span>, <span class="dv">2021</span>: <span class="fl">271.0</span>, <span class="dv">2022</span>: <span class="fl">292.7</span>, <span class="dv">2023</span>: <span class="fl">304.7</span>, <span class="dv">2024</span>: <span class="fl">314.0</span>,</span>
<span id="cb10-262"><a href="#cb10-262" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="dv">2025</span>: <span class="fl">322.0</span></span>
<span id="cb10-263"><a href="#cb10-263" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>}</span>
<span id="cb10-264"><a href="#cb10-264" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-265"><a href="#cb10-265" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="kw">def</span> adjust_for_inflation(row):</span>
<span id="cb10-266"><a href="#cb10-266" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    year <span class="op">=</span> row[<span class="st">&#39;release_date&#39;</span>].year</span>
<span id="cb10-267"><a href="#cb10-267" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="cf">if</span> year <span class="kw">in</span> cpi_data:</span>
<span id="cb10-268"><a href="#cb10-268" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>        <span class="cf">return</span> row[<span class="st">&#39;budget&#39;</span>] <span class="op">*</span> (cpi_data[<span class="dv">2025</span>] <span class="op">/</span> cpi_data[year])</span>
<span id="cb10-269"><a href="#cb10-269" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="cf">return</span> row[<span class="st">&#39;budget&#39;</span>]</span>
<span id="cb10-270"><a href="#cb10-270" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-271"><a href="#cb10-271" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Apply inflation adjustment to the main dataframe</span></span>
<span id="cb10-272"><a href="#cb10-272" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data[<span class="st">&#39;budget_adjusted&#39;</span>] <span class="op">=</span> data.<span class="bu">apply</span>(adjust_for_inflation, axis<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">1</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-273"><a href="#cb10-273" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-274"><a href="#cb10-274" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Calculate median nominal and adjusted budget per year</span></span>
<span id="cb10-275"><a href="#cb10-275" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>budget_evolution <span class="op">=</span> data.groupby(data[<span class="st">&#39;release_date&#39;</span>].dt.year)[[<span class="st">&#39;budget&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;budget_adjusted&#39;</span>]].median().reset_index()</span>
<span id="cb10-276"><a href="#cb10-276" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>budget_evolution.columns <span class="op">=</span> [<span class="st">&#39;year&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;Nominal Budget&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;Real Budget (2025 USD)&#39;</span>]</span>
<span id="cb10-277"><a href="#cb10-277" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-278"><a href="#cb10-278" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Melt for plotting</span></span>
<span id="cb10-279"><a href="#cb10-279" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>budget_evolution_melted <span class="op">=</span> budget_evolution.melt(<span class="st">&#39;year&#39;</span>, var_name<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;Budget Type&#39;</span>, value_name<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;Amount&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-280"><a href="#cb10-280" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-281"><a href="#cb10-281" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Create the plot</span></span>
<span id="cb10-282"><a href="#cb10-282" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>fig, ax <span class="op">=</span> plt.subplots(figsize<span class="op">=</span>(<span class="fl">8.25</span>, <span class="fl">4.5</span>))</span>
<span id="cb10-283"><a href="#cb10-283" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-284"><a href="#cb10-284" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>sns.lineplot(data<span class="op">=</span>budget_evolution_melted, x<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;year&#39;</span>, y<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;Amount&#39;</span>, hue<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;Budget Type&#39;</span>, ax<span class="op">=</span>ax, marker<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;o&#39;</span>, palette<span class="op">=</span>[<span class="st">&#39;purple&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;orange&#39;</span>])</span>
<span id="cb10-285"><a href="#cb10-285" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-286"><a href="#cb10-286" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Add a trend line for the Real Budget</span></span>
<span id="cb10-287"><a href="#cb10-287" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>sns.regplot(data<span class="op">=</span>budget_evolution, x<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;year&#39;</span>, y<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;Real Budget (2025 USD)&#39;</span>, ax<span class="op">=</span>ax, scatter<span class="op">=</span><span class="va">False</span>, color<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;red&#39;</span>, line_kws<span class="op">=</span>{<span class="st">&#39;linestyle&#39;</span>:<span class="st">&#39;--&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;linewidth&#39;</span>: <span class="fl">1.5</span>, <span class="st">&#39;label&#39;</span>: <span class="st">&#39;Trend (Real)&#39;</span>})</span>
<span id="cb10-288"><a href="#cb10-288" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-289"><a href="#cb10-289" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Customize plot</span></span>
<span id="cb10-290"><a href="#cb10-290" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_title(<span class="st">&quot;Median Movie Budget Evolution (1990-2025)&quot;</span>, </span>
<span id="cb10-291"><a href="#cb10-291" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>             fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">16</span>, fontweight<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;bold&#39;</span>, pad<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">15</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-292"><a href="#cb10-292" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_xlabel(<span class="st">&quot;Year&quot;</span>, fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">12</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-293"><a href="#cb10-293" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_ylabel(<span class="st">&quot;Median Budget (in USD)&quot;</span>, fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">12</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-294"><a href="#cb10-294" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.grid(<span class="va">True</span>, alpha<span class="op">=</span><span class="fl">0.5</span>, linestyle<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;--&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-295"><a href="#cb10-295" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.get_yaxis().set_major_formatter(plt.FuncFormatter(<span class="kw">lambda</span> x, p: <span class="ss">f&#39;$</span><span class="sc">{</span>x<span class="op">/</span><span class="dv">1_000_000</span><span class="sc">:.0f}</span><span class="ss">M&#39;</span>))</span>
<span id="cb10-296"><a href="#cb10-296" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.legend()</span>
<span id="cb10-297"><a href="#cb10-297" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-298"><a href="#cb10-298" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>plt.tight_layout()</span>
<span id="cb10-299"><a href="#cb10-299" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>plt.show()</span>
<span id="cb10-300"><a href="#cb10-300" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="in">```</span></span>
<span id="cb10-301"><a href="#cb10-301" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-302"><a href="#cb10-302" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>**Interpretation:**</span>
<span id="cb10-303"><a href="#cb10-303" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-304"><a href="#cb10-304" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>@fig-budget-evolution reveals a surprising divergence between nominal spending and real purchasing power. While the nominal budget (purple line) suggests a gradual increase from roughly $11 million in 1990 to peaks of $30 million in recent years, the inflation-adjusted &quot;Real Budget&quot; (gold line, Base 2025) tells a starkly different story. Contrary to the expectation that costs have skyrocketed, the regression line indicates a clear downward trend in real median budgets over the 35-year period.</span>
<span id="cb10-305"><a href="#cb10-305" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-306"><a href="#cb10-306" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>In real terms (2025 dollars), median budgets actually peaked in the late 1990s, reaching highs of over $35 million. Since then, despite significant volatility, the purchasing power allocated to the median film has steadily eroded, dropping to approximately $19 million by 2025.</span>
<span id="cb10-307"><a href="#cb10-307" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-308"><a href="#cb10-308" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>Several factors may explain this real-term decline. First, the democratization of digital filmmaking tools may have lowered the barrier to entry, allowing more low-to-mid-budget films to be produced more cheaply. Second, the industry may be experiencing a &quot;hollowing out&quot; effect: while massive blockbusters (not captured by the median) have ballooned in cost, the &quot;middle-class&quot; movie has faced tightening budget constraints.</span>
<span id="cb10-309"><a href="#cb10-309" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-310"><a href="#cb10-310" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>The graph also highlights distinct periods of volatility. A sharp dip is visible around the 2008 financial crisis and again in the mid-2010s. Interestingly, while there was a significant spike in real spending around 2022–2023 (likely a post-pandemic production surge) values have since corrected downward. Overall, the analysis overturns the assumption that filmmaking is becoming universally more expensive; instead, it suggests that outside of mega-blockbusters, the typical film is being made with a leaner real-world budget than it was three decades ago.</span>
<span id="cb10-311"><a href="#cb10-311" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-312"><a href="#cb10-312" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">## Q3: To what extent does financial investment (budget) influence audience reception (IMDb rating)?</span></span>
<span id="cb10-313"><a href="#cb10-313" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-314"><a href="#cb10-314" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>A central question for any film producer is whether more money leads to a better movie. We investigate this by plotting **inflation-adjusted budgets** against their IMDb ratings. Given that budgets span several orders of magnitude, we use a logarithmic scale for the budget axis to better visualize the relationship.</span>
<span id="cb10-315"><a href="#cb10-315" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-318"><a href="#cb10-318" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="in">```{python}</span></span>
<span id="cb10-319"><a href="#cb10-319" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#| label: fig-budget-rating-correlation</span></span>
<span id="cb10-320"><a href="#cb10-320" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#| fig-cap: &quot;Scatter plot of inflation-adjusted movie budget vs. IMDb rating&quot;</span></span>
<span id="cb10-321"><a href="#cb10-321" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-322"><a href="#cb10-322" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Filter out rows with missing budget or rating for this analysis</span></span>
<span id="cb10-323"><a href="#cb10-323" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>budget_rating_data <span class="op">=</span> data.dropna(subset<span class="op">=</span>[<span class="st">&#39;budget_adjusted&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;rating&#39;</span>])</span>
<span id="cb10-324"><a href="#cb10-324" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-325"><a href="#cb10-325" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Create the plot</span></span>
<span id="cb10-326"><a href="#cb10-326" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>fig, ax <span class="op">=</span> plt.subplots(figsize<span class="op">=</span>(<span class="fl">8.25</span>, <span class="fl">5.25</span>))</span>
<span id="cb10-327"><a href="#cb10-327" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-328"><a href="#cb10-328" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>sns.regplot(data<span class="op">=</span>budget_rating_data, x<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;budget_adjusted&#39;</span>, y<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;rating&#39;</span>,</span>
<span id="cb10-329"><a href="#cb10-329" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>            ax<span class="op">=</span>ax, scatter_kws<span class="op">=</span>{<span class="st">&#39;alpha&#39;</span>: <span class="fl">0.2</span>, <span class="st">&#39;s&#39;</span>: <span class="dv">20</span>},</span>
<span id="cb10-330"><a href="#cb10-330" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>            line_kws<span class="op">=</span>{<span class="st">&#39;color&#39;</span>: <span class="st">&#39;red&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;linewidth&#39;</span>: <span class="dv">2</span>})</span>
<span id="cb10-331"><a href="#cb10-331" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-332"><a href="#cb10-332" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Customize plot</span></span>
<span id="cb10-333"><a href="#cb10-333" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_xscale(<span class="st">&#39;log&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-334"><a href="#cb10-334" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_title(<span class="st">&quot;Correlation Between Real Budget and IMDb Rating&quot;</span>, </span>
<span id="cb10-335"><a href="#cb10-335" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>             fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">16</span>, fontweight<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;bold&#39;</span>, pad<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">15</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-336"><a href="#cb10-336" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_xlabel(<span class="st">&quot;Budget (Inflation Adjusted to 2025 USD, log scale)&quot;</span>, fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">12</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-337"><a href="#cb10-337" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_ylabel(<span class="st">&quot;IMDb Rating&quot;</span>, fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">12</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-338"><a href="#cb10-338" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.grid(<span class="va">True</span>, alpha<span class="op">=</span><span class="fl">0.3</span>, linestyle<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;--&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-339"><a href="#cb10-339" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-340"><a href="#cb10-340" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Add correlation coefficient</span></span>
<span id="cb10-341"><a href="#cb10-341" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>correlation <span class="op">=</span> budget_rating_data[<span class="st">&#39;budget_adjusted&#39;</span>].corr(budget_rating_data[<span class="st">&#39;rating&#39;</span>])</span>
<span id="cb10-342"><a href="#cb10-342" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.text(<span class="fl">0.05</span>, <span class="fl">0.95</span>, <span class="ss">f&#39;Pearson Correlation: </span><span class="sc">{</span>correlation<span class="sc">:.3f}</span><span class="ss">&#39;</span>, </span>
<span id="cb10-343"><a href="#cb10-343" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>        transform<span class="op">=</span>ax.transAxes, fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">11</span>,</span>
<span id="cb10-344"><a href="#cb10-344" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>        verticalalignment<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;top&#39;</span>,</span>
<span id="cb10-345"><a href="#cb10-345" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>        bbox<span class="op">=</span><span class="bu">dict</span>(boxstyle<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;round&#39;</span>, facecolor<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;wheat&#39;</span>, alpha<span class="op">=</span><span class="fl">0.5</span>))</span>
<span id="cb10-346"><a href="#cb10-346" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-347"><a href="#cb10-347" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>plt.tight_layout()</span>
<span id="cb10-348"><a href="#cb10-348" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>plt.show()</span>
<span id="cb10-349"><a href="#cb10-349" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="in">```</span></span>
<span id="cb10-350"><a href="#cb10-350" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-351"><a href="#cb10-351" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>**Interpretation:**</span>
<span id="cb10-352"><a href="#cb10-352" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-353"><a href="#cb10-353" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>@fig-budget-rating-correlation demonstrates that there is an extremely weak relationship between a film&#39;s inflation-adjusted budget and its IMDb rating. While the regression curve (red line) shows a slight upward inflection at the highest budget levels, the overall pattern is largely flat. This visual observation is confirmed by the low Pearson correlation coefficient of 0.140, indicating only a minimal linear association between financial investment and audience reception.</span>
<span id="cb10-354"><a href="#cb10-354" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-355"><a href="#cb10-355" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>The dispersion of points across the logarithmic budget scale further supports this conclusion. Highly rated films (with scores above 7 or 8) appear across the entire financial spectrum, ranging from micro-budget productions costing less than $10,000 (roughly $10^4$) to massive blockbusters exceeding $200–300 million. Likewise, low-rated films are distributed widely. This significant vertical spread suggests that audience appreciation depends far more on qualitative factors (such as storytelling, acting, and originality) than on the magnitude of resources spent.</span>
<span id="cb10-356"><a href="#cb10-356" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-357"><a href="#cb10-357" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>However, a subtle pattern emerges at the extreme right of the plot: films with the highest inflation-adjusted budgets (approaching $10^8$ and above) tend to avoid the lowest rating range (scores below 4). In other words, while spending massive amounts does not guarantee a masterpiece, it appears to reduce the likelihood of a film being critically panned. This &quot;floor effect&quot; likely results from the extensive professional oversight, technical standards, and production value inherent in large-scale studio projects.</span>
<span id="cb10-358"><a href="#cb10-358" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-359"><a href="#cb10-359" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>Overall, this analysis confirms that larger budgets do not strictly correlate with higher ratings. The data highlights the critical success of numerous low-to-mid-budget films, proving that creativity can rival visual spectacle. For producers, this emphasizes that while money can ensure technical competence, it cannot buy audience satisfaction.</span>
<span id="cb10-360"><a href="#cb10-360" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-361"><a href="#cb10-361" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">## Q3a: Is there a correlation between a film&#39;s budget and its box office revenue?</span></span>
<span id="cb10-362"><a href="#cb10-362" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-363"><a href="#cb10-363" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>While budget may not predict audience ratings, it might be a better predictor of commercial success. We now examine the relationship between a film&#39;s **inflation-adjusted budget** and its **inflation-adjusted worldwide gross revenue**. This analysis helps determine whether higher investments typically yield higher financial returns.</span>
<span id="cb10-364"><a href="#cb10-364" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-367"><a href="#cb10-367" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="in">```{python}</span></span>
<span id="cb10-368"><a href="#cb10-368" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#| label: fig-budget-revenue-correlation</span></span>
<span id="cb10-369"><a href="#cb10-369" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#| fig-cap: &quot;Scatter plot of inflation-adjusted movie budget vs. worldwide gross revenue&quot;</span></span>
<span id="cb10-370"><a href="#cb10-370" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-371"><a href="#cb10-371" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Apply inflation adjustment to gross_worldwide</span></span>
<span id="cb10-372"><a href="#cb10-372" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="kw">def</span> adjust_gross_for_inflation(row):</span>
<span id="cb10-373"><a href="#cb10-373" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    year <span class="op">=</span> row[<span class="st">&#39;release_date&#39;</span>].year</span>
<span id="cb10-374"><a href="#cb10-374" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="cf">if</span> year <span class="kw">in</span> cpi_data <span class="kw">and</span> pd.notna(row[<span class="st">&#39;gross_worldwide&#39;</span>]):</span>
<span id="cb10-375"><a href="#cb10-375" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>        <span class="cf">return</span> row[<span class="st">&#39;gross_worldwide&#39;</span>] <span class="op">*</span> (cpi_data[<span class="dv">2025</span>] <span class="op">/</span> cpi_data[year])</span>
<span id="cb10-376"><a href="#cb10-376" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="cf">return</span> row[<span class="st">&#39;gross_worldwide&#39;</span>]</span>
<span id="cb10-377"><a href="#cb10-377" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-378"><a href="#cb10-378" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data[<span class="st">&#39;gross_adjusted&#39;</span>] <span class="op">=</span> data.<span class="bu">apply</span>(adjust_gross_for_inflation, axis<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">1</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-379"><a href="#cb10-379" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-380"><a href="#cb10-380" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Filter out rows with missing budget or gross for this analysis</span></span>
<span id="cb10-381"><a href="#cb10-381" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>budget_revenue_data <span class="op">=</span> data.dropna(subset<span class="op">=</span>[<span class="st">&#39;budget_adjusted&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;gross_adjusted&#39;</span>])</span>
<span id="cb10-382"><a href="#cb10-382" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-383"><a href="#cb10-383" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Create the plot</span></span>
<span id="cb10-384"><a href="#cb10-384" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>fig, ax <span class="op">=</span> plt.subplots(figsize<span class="op">=</span>(<span class="fl">8.25</span>, <span class="fl">5.25</span>))</span>
<span id="cb10-385"><a href="#cb10-385" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-386"><a href="#cb10-386" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>sns.regplot(data<span class="op">=</span>budget_revenue_data, x<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;budget_adjusted&#39;</span>, y<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;gross_adjusted&#39;</span>,</span>
<span id="cb10-387"><a href="#cb10-387" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>            ax<span class="op">=</span>ax, scatter_kws<span class="op">=</span>{<span class="st">&#39;alpha&#39;</span>: <span class="fl">0.3</span>, <span class="st">&#39;s&#39;</span>: <span class="dv">20</span>},</span>
<span id="cb10-388"><a href="#cb10-388" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>            line_kws<span class="op">=</span>{<span class="st">&#39;color&#39;</span>: <span class="st">&#39;red&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;linewidth&#39;</span>: <span class="dv">2</span>})</span>
<span id="cb10-389"><a href="#cb10-389" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-390"><a href="#cb10-390" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Add a diagonal reference line (break-even line where gross = budget)</span></span>
<span id="cb10-391"><a href="#cb10-391" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>max_val <span class="op">=</span> <span class="bu">max</span>(budget_revenue_data[<span class="st">&#39;budget_adjusted&#39;</span>].<span class="bu">max</span>(), budget_revenue_data[<span class="st">&#39;gross_adjusted&#39;</span>].<span class="bu">max</span>())</span>
<span id="cb10-392"><a href="#cb10-392" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.plot([<span class="fl">1e4</span>, max_val], [<span class="fl">1e4</span>, max_val], <span class="st">&#39;k--&#39;</span>, linewidth<span class="op">=</span><span class="fl">1.5</span>, alpha<span class="op">=</span><span class="fl">0.8</span>, label<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;Break-even (Gross = Budget)&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-393"><a href="#cb10-393" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-394"><a href="#cb10-394" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Customize plot</span></span>
<span id="cb10-395"><a href="#cb10-395" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_xscale(<span class="st">&#39;log&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-396"><a href="#cb10-396" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_yscale(<span class="st">&#39;log&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-397"><a href="#cb10-397" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_title(<span class="st">&quot;Correlation Between Real Budget and Worldwide Gross Revenue&quot;</span>, </span>
<span id="cb10-398"><a href="#cb10-398" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>             fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">16</span>, fontweight<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;bold&#39;</span>, pad<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">15</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-399"><a href="#cb10-399" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_xlabel(<span class="st">&quot;Budget (Inflation Adjusted to 2025 USD, log scale)&quot;</span>, fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">12</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-400"><a href="#cb10-400" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_ylabel(<span class="st">&quot;Worldwide Gross (Inflation Adjusted to 2025 USD, log scale)&quot;</span>, fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">12</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-401"><a href="#cb10-401" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.grid(<span class="va">True</span>, alpha<span class="op">=</span><span class="fl">0.3</span>, linestyle<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;--&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-402"><a href="#cb10-402" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-403"><a href="#cb10-403" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Add correlation coefficient</span></span>
<span id="cb10-404"><a href="#cb10-404" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>correlation_revenue <span class="op">=</span> budget_revenue_data[<span class="st">&#39;budget_adjusted&#39;</span>].corr(budget_revenue_data[<span class="st">&#39;gross_adjusted&#39;</span>])</span>
<span id="cb10-405"><a href="#cb10-405" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.text(<span class="fl">0.05</span>, <span class="fl">0.95</span>, <span class="ss">f&#39;Pearson Correlation: </span><span class="sc">{</span>correlation_revenue<span class="sc">:.3f}</span><span class="ss">&#39;</span>, </span>
<span id="cb10-406"><a href="#cb10-406" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>        transform<span class="op">=</span>ax.transAxes, fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">11</span>,</span>
<span id="cb10-407"><a href="#cb10-407" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>        verticalalignment<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;top&#39;</span>,</span>
<span id="cb10-408"><a href="#cb10-408" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>        bbox<span class="op">=</span><span class="bu">dict</span>(boxstyle<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;round&#39;</span>, facecolor<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;wheat&#39;</span>, alpha<span class="op">=</span><span class="fl">0.5</span>))</span>
<span id="cb10-409"><a href="#cb10-409" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-410"><a href="#cb10-410" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.legend(loc<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;lower right&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-411"><a href="#cb10-411" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>plt.tight_layout()</span>
<span id="cb10-412"><a href="#cb10-412" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>plt.show()</span>
<span id="cb10-413"><a href="#cb10-413" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="in">```</span></span>
<span id="cb10-414"><a href="#cb10-414" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-415"><a href="#cb10-415" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>**Interpretation:**</span>
<span id="cb10-416"><a href="#cb10-416" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-417"><a href="#cb10-417" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>@fig-budget-revenue-correlation reveals a **strong positive correlation** between a film&#39;s inflation-adjusted budget and its worldwide gross revenue, with a Pearson correlation coefficient of approximately 0.74–0.78. This stands in stark contrast to the near-zero correlation observed between budget and IMDb rating in the previous section.</span>
<span id="cb10-418"><a href="#cb10-418" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-419"><a href="#cb10-419" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>Several key observations emerge from this analysis:</span>
<span id="cb10-420"><a href="#cb10-420" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-421"><a href="#cb10-421" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">1. </span>**Strong Linear Relationship**: The upward-sloping regression line (red) demonstrates that, on average, films with higher budgets tend to generate higher box office revenues. This relationship is visually apparent and statistically significant.</span>
<span id="cb10-422"><a href="#cb10-422" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-423"><a href="#cb10-423" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">2. </span>**Break-Even Analysis**: The black dashed line represents the break-even point where gross revenue equals the production budget. Most data points cluster above this line, indicating that the majority of films in our dataset recouped their production costs at the box office. However, it&#39;s important to note that this does not account for marketing costs (often 50-100% of the production budget) or distribution fees, meaning true profitability is harder to determine.</span>
<span id="cb10-424"><a href="#cb10-424" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-425"><a href="#cb10-425" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">3. </span>**Variance at Higher Budgets**: While the correlation is strong, there is considerable variance, especially at higher budget levels. Some high-budget films ($100M+) achieve extraordinary returns (appearing well above the regression line), while others underperform relative to their investment. This variance reflects the inherent risk in blockbuster filmmaking—while big budgets can lead to big returns, they can also result in significant losses.</span>
<span id="cb10-426"><a href="#cb10-426" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-427"><a href="#cb10-427" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ss">4. </span>**Low-Budget Outliers**: Several low-budget films (below $10M) show remarkable returns, appearing far above the break-even line. These represent the &quot;indie success stories&quot;—films that achieved commercial success disproportionate to their modest investments, often through word-of-mouth, critical acclaim, or viral marketing.</span>
<span id="cb10-428"><a href="#cb10-428" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-429"><a href="#cb10-429" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>**Key Takeaway**: While money cannot buy audience appreciation (as shown in Q3), it does correlate strongly with commercial performance. This makes intuitive sense: larger budgets enable wider theatrical releases, more extensive marketing campaigns, bigger stars, and higher production values that attract audiences to theaters. However, the scatter around the trend line reminds us that financial success is never guaranteed—storytelling, timing, and market conditions all play crucial roles.</span>
<span id="cb10-430"><a href="#cb10-430" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-431"><a href="#cb10-431" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">## Q4: How has the typical duration of feature films evolved over the last three decades?</span></span>
<span id="cb10-432"><a href="#cb10-432" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-433"><a href="#cb10-433" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>Have you ever felt that movies are getting longer? This analysis investigates whether there is data to support this common perception. We plot the average movie duration per year to see if a trend emerges.</span>
<span id="cb10-434"><a href="#cb10-434" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-437"><a href="#cb10-437" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="in">```{python}</span></span>
<span id="cb10-438"><a href="#cb10-438" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#| label: fig-duration-evolution</span></span>
<span id="cb10-439"><a href="#cb10-439" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#| fig-cap: &quot;Average movie duration (in minutes) from 1990 to 2025&quot;</span></span>
<span id="cb10-440"><a href="#cb10-440" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-441"><a href="#cb10-441" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Calculate average duration per year</span></span>
<span id="cb10-442"><a href="#cb10-442" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>avg_duration_per_year <span class="op">=</span> data.groupby(data[<span class="st">&#39;release_date&#39;</span>].dt.year)[<span class="st">&#39;duration_minutes&#39;</span>].mean().reset_index()</span>
<span id="cb10-443"><a href="#cb10-443" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>avg_duration_per_year.columns <span class="op">=</span> [<span class="st">&#39;year&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;avg_duration&#39;</span>]</span>
<span id="cb10-444"><a href="#cb10-444" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-445"><a href="#cb10-445" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Create the plot</span></span>
<span id="cb10-446"><a href="#cb10-446" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>fig, ax <span class="op">=</span> plt.subplots(figsize<span class="op">=</span>(<span class="fl">8.25</span>, <span class="fl">4.5</span>))</span>
<span id="cb10-447"><a href="#cb10-447" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-448"><a href="#cb10-448" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>sns.lineplot(data<span class="op">=</span>avg_duration_per_year, x<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;year&#39;</span>, y<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;avg_duration&#39;</span>, ax<span class="op">=</span>ax, marker<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;.&#39;</span>, color<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;darkgreen&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-449"><a href="#cb10-449" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-450"><a href="#cb10-450" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Add a trend line to show the overall increase</span></span>
<span id="cb10-451"><a href="#cb10-451" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>sns.regplot(data<span class="op">=</span>avg_duration_per_year, x<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;year&#39;</span>, y<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;avg_duration&#39;</span>, ax<span class="op">=</span>ax, scatter<span class="op">=</span><span class="va">False</span>, color<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;red&#39;</span>, line_kws<span class="op">=</span>{<span class="st">&#39;linestyle&#39;</span>:<span class="st">&#39;--&#39;</span>})</span>
<span id="cb10-452"><a href="#cb10-452" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-453"><a href="#cb10-453" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Customize plot</span></span>
<span id="cb10-454"><a href="#cb10-454" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_title(<span class="st">&quot;Average Movie Duration Evolution (1990-2025)&quot;</span>, </span>
<span id="cb10-455"><a href="#cb10-455" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>             fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">16</span>, fontweight<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;bold&#39;</span>, pad<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">15</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-456"><a href="#cb10-456" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_xlabel(<span class="st">&quot;Year&quot;</span>, fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">12</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-457"><a href="#cb10-457" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.set_ylabel(<span class="st">&quot;Average Duration (minutes)&quot;</span>, fontsize<span class="op">=</span><span class="dv">12</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-458"><a href="#cb10-458" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>ax.grid(<span class="va">True</span>, alpha<span class="op">=</span><span class="fl">0.5</span>, linestyle<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;--&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-459"><a href="#cb10-459" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-460"><a href="#cb10-460" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>plt.tight_layout()</span>
<span id="cb10-461"><a href="#cb10-461" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>plt.show()</span>
<span id="cb10-462"><a href="#cb10-462" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="in">```</span></span>
<span id="cb10-463"><a href="#cb10-463" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-464"><a href="#cb10-464" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>**Interpretation:**</span>
<span id="cb10-465"><a href="#cb10-465" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-466"><a href="#cb10-466" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>@fig-duration-evolution shows that the average duration of films has gradually increased over the last 3 decades. While films averaged around 102–104 minutes in the early 1990s, in recent years the average has more frequently reached 106–108 minutes, with some peaks even higher.</span>
<span id="cb10-467"><a href="#cb10-467" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-468"><a href="#cb10-468" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>A notable exception emerges between approximately 2004 and 2012, during which time the average runtime decreases by several minutes compared to preceding and subsequent periods. This decline could be due to a number of factors, such as the increased popularity of mid-budget commercial comedies and action films, which tend to be shorter, as well as increased studio pressure to reduce runtimes in order to fit in more daily theatrical showings. There was also a shift towards faster-paced storytelling during the early 2000s. There were also fewer very long &#39;epic-style&#39; releases during this period than in the later 2010s, which may have contributed to the lower averages.</span>
<span id="cb10-469"><a href="#cb10-469" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-470"><a href="#cb10-470" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>Although there are yearly fluctuations, likely due to changes in sample size or variations in genre popularity, the overall regression trend line confirms a steady increase throughout the period.</span>
<span id="cb10-471"><a href="#cb10-471" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-472"><a href="#cb10-472" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>This rise is modest rather than dramatic, but it is consistent, indicating that films today are generally a few minutes longer than those produced in the 1990s. This shift may reflect broader industry trends, such as the growth of franchise-based &#39;event movies&#39;, which often have longer narratives. The expansion of streaming platforms may also be a contributing factor: without the physical constraints imposed by VHS, DVDs or theatrical scheduling, filmmakers have greater freedom to determine runtime.</span>
<span id="cb10-473"><a href="#cb10-473" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-474"><a href="#cb10-474" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>Overall, the data supports the idea that films have become slightly longer over time. While the increase is not extreme, it signals a shift in storytelling practices, with modern productions tending to embrace more complex or expansive narratives than in previous decades.</span>
<span id="cb10-475"><a href="#cb10-475" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-476"><a href="#cb10-476" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">## Q5: Which countries have dominated global film production?</span></span>
<span id="cb10-477"><a href="#cb10-477" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-478"><a href="#cb10-478" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>To understand the geographical landscape of the film industry, we identify the top movie-producing countries for each decade (from the 1990s to the 2020s). This helps reveal the centers of film production and how their influence has evolved.</span>
<span id="cb10-479"><a href="#cb10-479" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-482"><a href="#cb10-482" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="in">```{python}</span></span>
<span id="cb10-483"><a href="#cb10-483" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#| label: fig-country-production</span></span>
<span id="cb10-484"><a href="#cb10-484" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#| fig-cap: &quot;Top 5 movie-producing countries by decade&quot;</span></span>
<span id="cb10-485"><a href="#cb10-485" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-486"><a href="#cb10-486" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># The &#39;countries_origin&#39; is a string representation of a list. We need to parse it.</span></span>
<span id="cb10-487"><a href="#cb10-487" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># We&#39;ll take the first country as the primary country of origin.</span></span>
<span id="cb10-488"><a href="#cb10-488" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="kw">def</span> get_first_country(countries_str):</span>
<span id="cb10-489"><a href="#cb10-489" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="cf">if</span> pd.isna(countries_str):</span>
<span id="cb10-490"><a href="#cb10-490" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>        <span class="cf">return</span> <span class="va">None</span></span>
<span id="cb10-491"><a href="#cb10-491" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="cf">try</span>:</span>
<span id="cb10-492"><a href="#cb10-492" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>        countries_list <span class="op">=</span> ast.literal_eval(countries_str)</span>
<span id="cb10-493"><a href="#cb10-493" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>        <span class="cf">if</span> countries_list:</span>
<span id="cb10-494"><a href="#cb10-494" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>            <span class="cf">return</span> countries_list[<span class="dv">0</span>]</span>
<span id="cb10-495"><a href="#cb10-495" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="cf">except</span> (<span class="pp">ValueError</span>, <span class="pp">SyntaxError</span>):</span>
<span id="cb10-496"><a href="#cb10-496" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>        <span class="cf">return</span> <span class="va">None</span></span>
<span id="cb10-497"><a href="#cb10-497" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="cf">return</span> <span class="va">None</span></span>
<span id="cb10-498"><a href="#cb10-498" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-499"><a href="#cb10-499" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>data[<span class="st">&#39;primary_country&#39;</span>] <span class="op">=</span> data[<span class="st">&#39;countries_origin&#39;</span>].<span class="bu">apply</span>(get_first_country)</span>
<span id="cb10-500"><a href="#cb10-500" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-501"><a href="#cb10-501" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Get the top 5 countries per decade</span></span>
<span id="cb10-502"><a href="#cb10-502" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>top_countries_per_decade <span class="op">=</span> (</span>
<span id="cb10-503"><a href="#cb10-503" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    data.dropna(subset<span class="op">=</span>[<span class="st">&#39;primary_country&#39;</span>])</span>
<span id="cb10-504"><a href="#cb10-504" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    .groupby([<span class="st">&#39;decade&#39;</span>, <span class="st">&#39;primary_country&#39;</span>])</span>
<span id="cb10-505"><a href="#cb10-505" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    .size()</span>
<span id="cb10-506"><a href="#cb10-506" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    .reset_index(name<span class="op">=</span><span class="st">&#39;count&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-507"><a href="#cb10-507" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    .groupby(<span class="st">&#39;decade&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-508"><a href="#cb10-508" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    .<span class="bu">apply</span>(<span class="kw">lambda</span> x: x.nlargest(<span class="dv">5</span>, <span class="st">&#39;count&#39;</span>))</span>
