<span id="cb10-530"><a href="#cb10-530" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-531"><a href="#cb10-531" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>The bar chart in @fig-country-production allows us to have a clear picture of global film production leadership. We can see that the United States (Hollywood) has been the undisputed leader in film production across every decade since 1990, producing significantly more films than any other country. </span>
<span id="cb10-532"><a href="#cb10-532" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-533"><a href="#cb10-533" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>It also shows us that the constant second position holder is the United Kingdom, demonstrating its strong and stable film industry. The consistent presence of the UK, often as a co-production partner with the US, underscores its pivotal role. </span>
<span id="cb10-534"><a href="#cb10-534" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-535"><a href="#cb10-535" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>Other notable producers include India, France, and Canada, though their rankings shift between the 3rd, 4th, and 5th positions across decades. The strong showing from India (Bollywood) and the rise of China illustrate the globalization of cinema and the increasing importance of non-Western markets.</span>
<span id="cb10-536"><a href="#cb10-536" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-537"><a href="#cb10-537" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>A key trend to highlight is the emergence of China as a top producer in the 2010s and 2020s, reflecting the massive growth of its domestic film market. But Hong Kong&#39;s decline after ranking among the top five films in the 1990s shows a change in Asian film production.</span>
<span id="cb10-538"><a href="#cb10-538" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-539"><a href="#cb10-539" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>It is once again crucial to reiterate the geographical bias mentioned in our data section; while the US appears overwhelmingly dominant, this dataset likely underrepresents the volume of film production from regions. It can be, for instance,  Nollywood (Nigeria) or other prolific non-English language industries, as their data may be less comprehensively captured on IMDb.</span>
<span id="cb10-540"><a href="#cb10-540" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-541"><a href="#cb10-541" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">## Q6: Do the highest-rated films consistently come from the same regions?</span></span>
<span id="cb10-542"><a href="#cb10-542" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-543"><a href="#cb10-543" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>Finally, we investigate whether critical acclaim is concentrated in specific regions. We filter for &quot;top-tier&quot; movies (IMDb rating of 8.0 or higher) and analyze their countries of origin.</span>
<span id="cb10-544"><a href="#cb10-544" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-547"><a href="#cb10-547" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="in">```{python}</span></span>
<span id="cb10-548"><a href="#cb10-548" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#| label: fig-top-rated-countries</span></span>
<span id="cb10-549"><a href="#cb10-549" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#| fig-cap: &quot;Origin countries of top-rated movies (IMDb Rating &gt;= 8.0)&quot;</span></span>
<span id="cb10-550"><a href="#cb10-550" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb10-551"><a href="#cb10-551" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Filter for top-rated movies</span></span>
<span id="cb10-552"><a href="#cb10-552" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>top_rated_movies <span class="op">=</span> data[data[<span class="st">&#39;rating&#39;</span>] <span class="op">&gt;=</span> <span class="fl">8.0</span>].dropna(subset<span class="op">=</span>[<span class="st">&#39;primary_country&#39;</span>])</span>
